An atom of the chemical element Argon. [Allotrope]

Value representation for arrays or variable length types. [Allotrope]

An atom is a smallest particle still characterizing a chemical element. It consists of a nucleus of a positive charge carrying almost all its mass (more than 99.9%) and Z electrons determining its size. [IUPAC]

A spatial change state the decreases the spatial distance at the end. [Allotrope]

Attributes are small named datasets that are attached to primary datasets, groups, or named datatypes. Attributes can be used to describe the nature and/or the intended usage of a dataset or group. An attribute has two parts: (1) a name and (2) a value. The value part contains one or more data entries of the same datatype. [Allotrope]
The specification of component properties which represent attributes of observations in the cube, e.g. unit of measurement. [Allotrope]
An unintended or unpleasant sound that emanates from a device. [NCI]

Base 2 logarithm. [Allotrope]

A material role of an expected but not desired product of a synthesis. [Allotrope]
Examples: the leaving group in a de-protection step.

Definition: A device in which the sample is first introduced into a chamber (loop), temporarily isolated from the mobile phase system by valves, which can be switched to make an instantaneous diversion of the mobile phase stream through the chamber to carry the sample to the column. [IUPAC]
Source: L.S. Ettre, "Nomenclature for Chromatography", Pure & Appl. Chem. 1993, Vol. 65, No. 4, pp. 819-872

Definition: A calcium analysis document (cell-culture) is a document that encompasses the information associated with calcium. [Allotrope]

A datum that is the result of some calculation. [Allotrope]

A calculation description is a description that describes how a calculation was done. [Allotrope]

Calibration is the comparison of measurement values delivered by a device under test with those of a calibration standard of known accuracy. [Wikipedia]
Calibration is the comparison of measurement values delivered by a device under test with those of a calibration standard of known accuracy. [Wikipedia]
Source: JCGM 200:2008 International vocabulary of metrology — Basic and general concepts and associated terms (VIM)

Definition: A calibration algorithm is an algorithm about calibration that specifies the way a calibration curve is generated. [Allotrope]
The calibration assessment is an assessment about the calibrated instrument whether it is within the specification of the calibration method. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: calibration curve id; standard curve identifier; standard curve id
Definition: A calibration curve identifier is an identifier that identifies a particular calibration curve. [Allotrope]
A calibration facet that is about a parameter for calibration. [Allotrope]
A calibration facet is a facet that is information about a calibration. [Allotrope]
The calibration frequency is the frequency of how often calibrations are done in a time interval. [Allotrope]
The calibration interval is the duration between two consecutive calibrations. [Allotrope]
The calibration item role is the role of a material that is used in calibration for testing a measurement device. [Allotrope]
The calibration level is number of calibration points used to fit a function to a calibration curve. [Allotrope]
A calibration point is a single calibration result at a specific test point (one or more reference values). [Allotrope]

A piece of apparatus that is used to measure the heat of chemical reactions or physical changes. [CHMO]
A measurement in which heat is measured as some chemical reaction or physical process occurs. [IUPAC]
Source: IUPAC. Compendium of Chemical Terminology, 2nd ed. (the "Gold Book"). Compiled by A. D. McNaught and A. Wilkinson. Blackwell Scientific Publications, Oxford (1997). Online version (2019-) created by S. J. Chalk. ISBN 0-9678550-9-8. https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.

Definition: A campus is a site that is the grounds of a school, hospital, or other institution. [Allotrope]

In computer science, canonicalization (sometimes standardization or normalization) is a process for converting data that has more than one possible representation into a standard, normal, or canonical form. This can be done to compare different representations for equivalence, to count the number of distinct data structures, to improve the efficiency of various algorithms by eliminating repeated calculations, or to make it possible to impose a meaningful sorting order. [Wikipedia]
A capability is a proposition that is about a function, role or quality realized under given conditions. [Allotrope]
A capability aggregate document is a document that aggregates capability documents. [Allotrope]
A capability document is a document that encompasses the information associated with some capability. [Allotrope]

A capability feature is a facet that defines the feature with the role of a description or classification of a property, characteristic or facet of some data with the role of specified capability. [Allotrope]
A capability specification specifies some function that the target of the specification inheres. This capability can be restricted to a specific situation. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: retention factor; mass distribution ratio; partition ratio; capacity ratio
Definition: The capacity factor is a chromatography peak facet that is a measure of the time the sample component resides in the stationary phase relative to the time it resides in the mobile phase: it expresses how much longer a sample component is retarded by the stationary phase than it would take to travel through the column with the velocity of the mobile phase. [IUPAC]
A capillary is a tube with a small diameter. [Allotrope]
A piece of apparatus that has the form of a tube with a diameter of less than a millimeter and hosts the stationary bed in chromatography. [CHMO]
A capillary electrophoresis is an electrophoresis which takes place in a capillary. [CHMO]
A capillary electrophoresis column is a type of column that is used in capillary electrophoresis. [Allotrope]
The capillary electrophoresis result is the result of a process of capillary electrophoresis. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: capillary high performance liquid chromatography; capillary-HPLC; capillary high pressure liquid chromatography; capillary HPLC; capillary high-pressure liquid chromatography
Definition: Column chromatography where the mobile phase is a liquid, the stationary phase consists of very small particles held in a tube of diameter less than a millimeter, and the inlet pressure is relatively high. [CHMO]
A capillary inner coating role is a coating role of a material that is a coating within a chromatography column. [Allotrope]
Chromatography which takes place in a separation capillary and where the mobile phase is a liquid. [CHMO]
A textual entity that describes a figure [IAO]
Examples: Figure 1: A system diagram describing the modules of the Hanalyzer.  Reading methods (green) take external sources of knowledge (blue) and extract information from them, either by parsing structured data or biomedical language processing to extract information from unstructured data.  Reading modules are responsible for tracking the provenance of all knowledge.  Reasoning methods (yellow) enrich the knowledge that results from reading by, for example, noting two genes that are annotated to the same ontology term or database entry.  All knowledge sources, read or reasoned, are assigned a reliability score, and all are combined using that score into a knowledge network (orange) that represents the integration of all sorts of relationship between a pair of genes and a combined reliability score.  A data network (also orange) is created from experimental results to be analyzed.  The reporting modules (pink) integrate the data and knowledge networks, producing visualizations that can be queried with the associated drill-down tool.

Definition: A one-carbon compound with formula CO2 in which the carbon is attached to each oxygen atom by a double bond. [CHEBI]
Carbon dioxide gas is a gas that is composed of carbon dioxide molecules. [Allotrope]
A carbon dioxide saturation is a ratio of the partial pressure of carbon dioxide to the barometric pressure, expressed as a percentage. [Allotrope]
A one-carbon compound in which the carbon is joined only to a single oxygen. [CHEBI]
Carbon monoxide gas is a gas that is composed of carbon monoxide molecules. [Allotrope]
A Cardinal scale is scale where the difference between two values can be measured and its meaning is independent of the absolute values. [Allotrope]
A carrier role is the role of a material entity that supports another material or information localization process by keeping it moving or holding it at place. [Allotrope]
Examples: nitrogen carrying a sample in gc; air carrying sound; a ship carrying goods

Definition: A carrying role is a role of an entity that is realized in a carrying process. [Allotrope]
Carrying is a state where a material entity, the carrier, supports the state of moving or keeping in place of another material or information. [Allotrope]

Catalymetric titration is he process of determining the quantity of a sample by adding measured increments of a titrant until the end-point is reached. The titration involves a catalyst, and the end-point is detected by the sudden increase or decrease in the rate of a reaction. [CHMO]

A catalyst role is a reagent role of a substance that increases the rate of a reaction without modifying the overall standard Gibbs energy change in the reaction; the process is called catalysis. The catalyst is both a reactant and product of the reaction. [IUPAC]
Source: PAC, 1996, 68, 155 (Glossary of terms used in chemical kinetics, including reaction dynamics.)

Definition: The cathode is the electrode that acts as negative pole if voltage is applied (place of reduction). [Allotrope]
A cation (+) is an ion with fewer electrons than protons, giving it a positive charge. [Wikipedia]
A chromatography column where the stationary phase is a cation exchanger. [CHMO]
A description of the cause-consequence relation of processes. [Allotrope]
Cause is the causal role of an information content entity that is about something causally dependent for another thing. [Allotrope]
A material entity of anatomical origin (part of or deriving from an organism) that has as its parts a maximally connected cell compartment surrounded by a plasma membrane. [CL]
Cell count is the amount of cells within a whole. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: off-line analyzer; cell counter device; cell density module; cell counter analyzer; cell viability module; cell counter instrument
Definition: A device used to count the number of cells present in known volume of sample to determine the overall concentration cells per unit volume. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: cell counting analysis; cell counter analysis
Definition: Cell counter assay is a cellular assay that uses various methods to quantify cells in a culture. [Allotrope]
A cell counter configuration is a device configuration of a cell counter device. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: cell counter measurement result; cell counter analysis result
Definition: A cell counter result is an assay result that is the result of a cell counter assay. [Allotrope]
A cell counter result data is a facet of a document about a cell counting assay that is about a some result of the cell counting assay. [Allotrope]
A cell counter parameter datum is a facet of a document about a cell counting assay that is about a some parameter of the cell counting assay. [Allotrope]
Cell counting is the counting of cells. [Allotrope]
A cell counting aggregate document is a document that aggregates cell counting documents. [Allotrope]
A cell counting document is a document that encompasses the information associated with a cell counting run. [Allotrope]
Cell density is the number density of a population of cells. [Allotrope]
Cell density dilution factor is a cell counter parameter data that describes the dilution factor of the solution prepared for the cell counting assay. [Allotrope]
Cell density measurement is a measurement of the number density of cells. [Allotrope]
A cell diameter is the diameter of a cell. [Allotrope]
A cell holder is a type of container for samples in spectrophotometers. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: path length; cell path length (datum); path length (datum)
Definition: A cell path length is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the length of the radiation path through the absorbing medium in a single-pass cell. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: path length; path length (quality); cell path length
Definition: The cell path length is the length of the radiation path through the absorbing medium in a single-pass cell. [IUPAC]
A cell path length setting is a control setting that specifies some cell path length. [Allotrope]
Cell type processing method is cell counter parameter data that describes the type of cells analyzed in the cell counting assay. [Allotrope]

An assay that generates data about the presence, quantity, structure, function, behavior, or activity of cells, or a process that occurs at a cellular level of anatomical granularity (includes subcellular structures and organelles). [VIVO-ISF]
An information content entity that consists of a CRID symbol and additional information about the CRID registry to which it belongs. [IAO]
Examples: The sentence "The article has Pubmed ID 12345." contains a CRID that has two parts: one part is the CRID symbol, which is '12345'; the other part denotes the CRID registry, which is Pubmed.

Definition: A CRID registry is a dataset of CRID records, each consisting of a CRID symbol and additional information which was recorded in the dataset through a assigning a centrally registered identifier process. [IAO]
Examples: PubMed is a CRID registry. It has a dataset of PubMed identifiers associated with journal articles.

Definition: A symbol that is part of a CRID and that is sufficient to look up a record from the CRID's registry. [IAO]
A centroid x-coordinate is a x-coordinate for the center point of some entity. [Allotrope]
A centroid y-coordinate is a y-coordinate for the center point of some entity. [Allotrope]

A certificate refers to the confirmation of certain characteristics of an object, person or organization. This confirmation is often, but not always, provided by some form of external review, education, assessment, or audit. Accreditation is a specific organization's process of certification. [Wikipedia]

A change II sign enabled setting is a data processing setting specifying that the sign of the II quadrant is flipped before the Fourier transform to cover Relay_2CH coefficients 1 0 -1 0 0 1 0 -1. [Allotrope]
A change rate end point setting is an end point determination setting that specifies the maximum change in weight per unit time. [Allotrope]
A changeset captures what was added, deleted and updated in an electronic record and the motivation why it was done. [Allotrope]
Changing is a processing by which an entity gains or looses parts, qualities, roles, dispositions, functions etc in a predetermined and fixed manner but maintains its identity. [Allotrope]
Changing is controlling a quality of energy in a predetermined and fixed manner. [NIST]
Changing is controlling a quality of the material in a predetermined and fixed manner. The identity of the material is maintained. [NIST]
A changing quality process profile is a quality process profile where the tracked quality changes over time. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: being unsteady; altering quality change; altering (state); unsteady (state); altering; changing; unsteady quality state; changing (state); unstable quality state; unstable (state)
Definition: A changing quality state is a state where a material's quality is changing continuously. [Allotrope]

A communication channel or channel, refers either to a physical transmission medium such as a wire, or to a logical connection over a multiplexed medium such as a radio channel. A channel is used to convey an information signal, for example a digital bit stream, from one or several senders (or transmitters) to one or several receivers. [Wikipedia]
Charge deconvolution is a data transformation of a spectrum representing multiply charged ions to singly charged or neutral masses. [Allotrope]
Charge state is a facet that is about the electrical charge of an ion. It is single or multiple and positive or negatively charged. [Allotrope]
Any technique for measuring charge transport. [CHMO]
Increasing the amount of energy in a system. [Allotrope]

Chelatometric titration is the process of determining the quantity of a sample (metal cation) by adding measured increments of a titrant (a chelating agent) until the end-point, at which essentially all of the sample has reacted, is reached. [CHMO]
A disposition of a portion of material to react with other materials in a specific way by nature of its chemical composition. [Allotrope]
A chemical document is a document that is about some chemical substance. [Allotrope]
Work resulting from the reactions by which substances are produced from or converted into other substances. [NIST]
Examples: A battery converts the flow of chemical energy into electical energy.

Definition: Formation of a new ion in the gas phase by the reaction of a neutral with an ion. The process may involve transfer of an electron, a proton, or other charged species between the reactants. [IUPAC]
ScopeNote: This term is not synonymous with chemi-ionization. [IUPAC]
Source: K. K. Murray, R. K. Boyd, M. N. Eberlin, G. J. Langley, L. Li and Y. Naito, Pure Appl. Chem., 2013, 85, 1515-1609

Definition: Formation of a new ion in the gas phase by the reaction of a neutral with an ion. The process may involve transfer of an electron, a proton, or other charged species between the reactants. [IUPAC]
ScopeNote: When a positive ion results from chemical ionization, the term may be used without qualification. When a negative ion results, the term negative ion chemical ionization should be used. [IUPAC]
Source: K. K. Murray, R. K. Boyd, M. N. Eberlin, G. J. Langley, L. Li and Y. Naito, Pure Appl. Chem., 2013, 85, 1515-1609

Definition: A chemical ionization source is an ion source that consists of a high-pressure ionization chamber containing a reagent gas (for example N2, O2 or H2O) which is ionized by high-energy electrons from a heated strip of metal and goes on to react with the analyte to ionize it. [CHMO]

A data set derived from chemical imaging consisting of a three-dimensional image where two axes describe the x and y spatial dimensions and the third dimension represents spectral wavelength. The image is obtained by stacking one image per spectral wavelength sequentially. [CHMO]

AltLabels: portion of mixed chemical substances; mixed chemical substances
Definition: A portion of chemical mixture is a chemical substance that is composed of chemical substances. [Allotrope]
A chemical name is the written name of a chemical substance that shows the names of each of its elements or subcompounds. [Allotrope]
A chemical reaction is a process that results in the interconversion of chemical species. [IUPAC]
ScopeNote: Chemical reactions may be elementary reactions or stepwise reactions. (It should be noted that this definition includes experimentally observable interconversions of conformers.) Detectable chemical reactions normally involve sets of molecular entities as indicated by this definition, but it is often conceptually convenient to use the term also for changes involving single molecular entities (i.e. 'microscopic chemical events'). [IUPAC]

Definition: A chemical reaction disposition is a disposition inhered in a reaction mixture. [Allotrope]

A chemical shift is a quality quantification facet quantifying the fractional variation of the resonance frequency of a nucleus in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy in consequence of its magnetic environment of a nucleus. The chemical shift of a nucleus, δ, is expressed as a ratio involving its frequency, ν_cpd, relative to that of a standard, ν_ref, and defined as: δ = (ν_cpd - ν_ref)/ν_ref. [IUPAC]
Source: IUPAC. Compendium of Chemical Terminology, 2nd ed. (the "Gold Book"). Compiled by A. D. McNaught and A. Wilkinson. Blackwell Scientific Publications, Oxford (1997)

Definition: The fractional variation of the resonance frequency of a nucleus in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy in consequence of its magnetic environment. [IUPAC]
A chemical substance is a portion of material that is matter of constant composition best characterized by the entities (molecules, formula units, atoms) it is composed of. [IUPAC]
Source: IUPAC. Compendium of Chemical Terminology, 2nd ed. (the "Gold Book"). Compiled by A. D. McNaught and A. Wilkinson. Blackwell Scientific Publications, Oxford (1997).

Definition: A chemical substance quality is a quality that inheres in some portion of chemical substance. [Allotrope]
A separation method where the components (in this case stereoisomers) are distributed between two chiral phases, one of which is stationary, while the other moves in a definite direction. [CHMO]

PrefLabel: chiral stationary phase high-performance liquid chromatography
AltLabels: HPLC on a chiral stationary phase; CSP-HPLC; chiral HPLC; CSP HPLC; chiral stationary phase high-pressure liquid chromatography
Definition: Column chromatography where the mobile phase is a liquid, the stationary phase consists of very small chiral particles and the inlet pressure is relatively high. [CHMO]
A chord length is the length between any two points on the edge of a particle, with an upper bound of the diameter of the particle. [Allotrope]
A chord length distribution data cube is a data cube that represents particle count binned by chord length over time. [Allotrope]
A chord length distribution profile is a profile of the distribution of chord lengths of particles over time. [Allotrope]
A chord modulus is the slope of the line drawn between two specified points on a stress-strain curve. [Allotrope]
A chord modulus document is a document that encompasses the information associated with a chord modulus. [Allotrope]
A chord selection setting is a control setting for a FBRM run that optimizes the analysis for small primary particles or larger agglomerates. [Allotrope]
A chromatogram is a distribution function of a detector signal (such as ion count or absorbance) versus time of acquisition or versus volume of analyte. [Allotrope]
A chromatogram data cube is a data cube that represents a chromatogram. [Allotrope]

A piece of apparatus, consisting of a mobile phase supply system, an injection or sampling system, a column, detector and a data acquisition/processing system, that is used to carry out chromatographic separations. [CHMO]
A chromatography detector is a detector that is used in chromatography as component of a chromatography system. [Allotrope]
A chromatographic packing is a solid heterogeneous mixture consisting of a substrate and stationary phase used in a chromatographic separation. [Allotrope]

A chromatographic peak asymmetry factor is a chromatography peak facet that is equivalent to the ratio of the time or volume from the center point of a peak to its trailing edge to that of its fronting edge at a specified peak height. [Allotrope]
A chromatographic peak facet that quantitates the degree of separation between two peaks of a chromatogram. [Allotrope]

PrefLabel: chromatographic peak resolution using Foley-Dorsey method
Definition: A chromatographic peak resolution that is calculated using peak widths from the Foley Dorsey equation for asymmetric peaks. [Allotrope]

PrefLabel: chromatographic peak resolution using baseline peak widths
AltLabels: chromatographic peak resolution by USP <621> using widths at baseline; chromatographic peak resolution calculated by the ASTM method
Definition: Chromatographic peak resolution that is calculated by the USP <621> method using peak widths measured at the baseline. [Allotrope]

PrefLabel: chromatographic peak resolution using peak width at half-height
AltLabels: chromatographic peak resolution calculated by EP; chromatographic peak resolution by USP using widths at half-height; chromatographic peak resolution calculated by JP-27
Definition: Chromatographic peak resolution that is calculated using peak widths measured at the half height. [Allotrope]

PrefLabel: chromatographic peak resolution using peak widths at 4.4 % height
AltLabels: chromatographic peak resolution using peak widths at 4.4% height
Definition: A chromatographic peak resolution that is calculated using peak widths at 4.4 % peak height. [Allotrope]

PrefLabel: chromatographic peak resolution using statistical moments
Definition: Chromatographic peak resolution that is calculated based on peak widths derived from the second statistical moment (peak variance). [Allotrope]
One of the portions of material between which the components to be separated are distributed in chromatography. [CHMO]
A chromatography is a separation where the components are distributed between two phases, one of which is stationary, while the other moves in a definite direction. [CHMO]
A chromatography column is a type of column that contains a stationary phase for chromatographic separation of compounds. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: chromatography column chemistry classification (datum); chromatography column chemistry type (datum); chromatography column chemistry classification
Definition: A chromatography column chemistry type is a classification datum that classifies a chromatography column by the stationary phase and/or chromatographic packing used. [Allotrope]
A chromatography column document is a document that encompasses the information associated with a chromatography column. [Allotrope]
A chromatography column fill type is a classification datum that classifies a chromatography column by the form of the stationary phase in the column. [Allotrope]
Examples: Packed, WCOT, PLOT, or SCOT

Definition: A chromatography column film thickness is a thickness datum that quantifies the thickness of the film coating in a chromatography column. [Allotrope]
A chromatography column length (datum) is a length datum that quantifies the length of a chromatography column. [Allotrope]
The length of a chromatography column bed. [Allotrope]
A column part number is a part number that denotes some class of chromatography columns. [Allotrope]
A chromatography column particle size is a particle size datum that quantifies the dimensions of packing particles in a chromatography column. [Allotrope]
A chromatography column separation mode is a classification datum that classifies a column by the type of chromatography it supports. [Allotrope]
A column serial number is an equipment serial number that identifies some chromatography column. [Allotrope]
Chromatography data processing is a data transformation on chromatograms. [Allotrope]
A chromatography data system is a data system that controls a chromatography system and processes data participating in a chromatography run. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: CDS method; chromatography data system project; CDS project
Definition: A chromatography data system method is a plan specification that specifies how a process is to be executed on a chromatography data system. [Allotrope]
A chromatography peak is a peak that results from a detector's response to the presence of an analyte in the mobile phase eluting from a column in chromatography. [Allotrope]
A chromatography peak facet is a facet of a chromatography peak. [Allotrope]
A chromatography peak type is a classification datum that classifies a chromatography peak by the role played by the substance it is a proxy for in the chromatographic process. [Allotrope]
ScopeNote: It is mainly used to determine if it is relevant to the particular analysis.
Examples: main component, mobile phase, excipient

Definition: A chromatography result is a result of a chromatography run. [Allotrope]
A chromatography separation type is a classification datum that classifies the underlying separation process used in the chromatographic process. [Allotrope]
Examples: reversed phase, ion exchange, normal phase, ligand

Definition: A parameter specification specific to a chromatography system. [Allotrope]

ChunkMode specifies whether I/O is to be performed as linked-chunk I/O or as multi-chunk I/O. This function overrides the HDF5 Library's internal algorithm for determining which mechanism to use.
When an application uses collective I/O with chunked storage, the HDF5 Library normally uses an internal algorithm to determine whether that I/O activity should be conducted as one linked-chunk I/O or as multi-chunk I/O. ChunkMode is provided so that an application can override the library's algorithm in circumstances where the library might lack the information needed to make an optimal decision. [HDF]

AltLabels: polarization rotation; angle of optical rotation
Definition: Circular birefringence is the angle through which plane polarized light is rotated clockwise, as seen when facing the light source, in passing through an optically active medium. [IUPAC]
Source: IUPAC Quantities, Units and Symbols in Physical Chemistry, 1993

AltLabels: CD spectra; circular dichroic spectra; circular dichroic spectrum; circular dichroism spectra; CD spectrum; circular dichroism (CD) spectra
Definition: A plot of ellipticity vs. wavelength obtained by measuring the differential absorption of left- and right-handed circularly polarized photon radiation as a function of wavelength. [CHMO]
A circularity is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the two-dimensional roundness of an entity. [Allotrope]
A circularity is a shape quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the two-dimensional roundness of an entity. [Allotrope]
A class coordination is a facet of a definition of a class that expresses some differentia. [Allotrope]
A type datum is a classification datum that classifies a thing as an instance of an RDFS class. [Allotrope]
A classification is a proposition that categorizes things into classes or collections of things differentiated by some criteria. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: classification facet; type datum; type facet
Definition: A classification datum is a facet that classifies some entity. [Allotrope]
A contextual role of information that classifies some of some entity into a category, class or schema. [Allotrope]
Cleaning is the process of getting rid of dirt, impurities, or extraneous unwanted matter. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: washing agent; detergent; detergent role; washing agent role
Definition: Cleaning agent role is a role of material used for cleaning something. [Allotrope]
The role of a participant of a cleaning process. [Allotrope]

A quantitative or qualitative value which is the result of an act of assessing a morphological or physiological state or property in a single individual or sample or a group of individuals or samples, based on direct observation or experimental manipulation. [CMO]
A clock is a measurement device used to measure, keep, and indicate time. [Wikipedia]

The closed loop uses feedback control for the regulation of the vapor generation. The system continuously detects deviations from the target partial pressure and adjusts the vapor generation correspondingly. [Allotrope]
A coated material description is a description of the material with the role of coated material. [Allotrope]
A coated material is a coating role of a material whose surface is being coated by another material which it covers. [Allotrope]
Coated state is the covering state when a substance covers the surface of another substance firmly. [Allotrope]
The application of a thin cover to a material. [CHMO]
A coating gap height is a height facet that quantifies the gap between the coating device and the material that is coated in the coating process. [Allotrope]
A coating process role is a role of a material that participates in a coating activity or the state of being coated. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: coating; coating medium; coating medium role
Definition: A coating role is the role of a material that coats another material (the substrate). [Allotrope]
An entry in a list of controlled symbols denoting a classification. [Allotrope]
A classification datum that classifies things by a code in a codelist. [Allotrope]
A code scan result is an assay result that is the output of a code scanning. [Allotrope]
Code scanning is the transformation of data in the representation form of visual machine-readable codes to another form. [Allotrope]
A set of codes in a controlled vocabulary. [Allotrope]
A codomain is the mathematical role of the set a function maps to. [Allotrope]
The act of gathering things together; having been brought together in one place. [NCI]
A collecting device is a device that has the function to collect things. [Allotrope]
A storing state that brings a flow together at one place. [NIST]
Examples: Solar panels collect ultraviolet sun rays to power small mechanisms. [NIST]

Definition: An aggregation of data items for a purpose. [Allotrope]
Collision energy is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the energy for an ion experiencing collision with a stationary gas particle resulting in dissociation of the ion. [PSI/MS]
Collision energy is energy for an ion experiencing collision with a stationary gas particle resulting in dissociation of the ion. [PSI/MS]

A colloid is a homogeneous mixture in which one substance of microscopically dispersed insoluble particles is suspended throughout another substance. A colloid has a dispersed phase (the suspended particles) and a continuous phase (the medium of suspension). The molecules or polymolecular particles dispersed in a medium have at least in one direction a dimension roughly between 1 nanometer and 1 micrometer, or in a system discontinuities are found at distances of that order. [IUPAC]
Source: PAC, 1972, 31, 577 (Manual of Symbols and Terminology for Physicochemical Quantities and Units, Appendix II: Definitions, Terminology and Symbols in Colloid and Surface Chemistry) on page 605

Definition: A color is a composite chromatic quality composed of hue, saturation and intensity parts. [PATO]
The determination of the spectral absorbance of a solution. This method is often used to determine the concentration of a chemical in a solution. [CHMO]
A column brand name is a brand name of a chromatography column that can be based on the brand name of the substrate and its chemistry modification. [Allotrope]

A chromatography method where the stationary bed is within a tube (of standard length 25 cm). The particles of the solid stationary phase or support coated with a liquid stationary phase may fill the whole inside volume of the tube (packed column) or be concentrated on or along the inside tube wall leaving an open, unrestricted path for the mobile phase in the middle part of the tube (open-tubular column). [CHMO]
A column compartment is a compartment in a chromatography system where the columns are held. [Allotrope]
A parameter specification specific to the column compartment in the chromatography system. [Allotrope]
A column compartment temperature setting is a temperature setting that specifies the temperature of some column compartment. [Allotrope]
A column inner diameter (datum) is an inner diameter quantifies the inner diameter of a column. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: dc; inner diameter; column inner diameter
Definition: Column inner diameter is the inner diameter of a column. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: column dead time; column dwell time; dwell time; void time; dead time; column void time
Definition: A column void volume time is the time required for an unretained compound to traverse the column and exit. [Allotrope]
A columnar particle shape is a shape of particle with similar moderate height and width and large length. [Allotrope]
ScopeNote: Columnar particles are similar in shape to poster tubes or wood joists.

Definition: Combining is the building of a whole out of parts. [Allotrope]
Combining material is a combing process that combines two or more materials in to a new material. [Allotrope]
A comment is a remark often related to an added piece of information, or an observation or statement. [SIO]
Base 10 logarithm. [Allotrope]

Communicating is transferring information from one material entity to another. This can be by way of a material or energy connecting the entity or by transporting the material bearing the information between the locations. [Allotrope]
A communication device is a device that has the function to communicate (transport information). [Allotrope]
A facet that is about communication channels. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: comparative cycle threshold qPCR experiment; comparative CT experiment; ∆∆CT
Definition: A comparative CT experiment is an experiment using qPCR that determines relative target quantity in samples.  Samples are compared to a normalized target quantity to determine relative quantity of the sample. [Allotrope]
ScopeNote: comparative CT

Definition: The observation or assessment of the similarities or dissimilarities between two things. [Allotrope]
A separate enclosed physical section of a device that can contain other devices. [Allotrope]
A compartment temperature is a quality quantification facet quantifying the temperature of some compartment. [Allotrope]
A completed state is a state during which a planned process has run to completion and the device or service is waiting for a reset that cause the state to change to an idle state. [Allotrope]
A factor with a complex number as value. [Allotrope]

A complex value order is an order function which is defined for component specifications with complex data types represented by shapes. It consists of a set of items each defining a property path of the shape, an order and an ordering function.
Thus, a complex value order can be considered as a set order orders specified for property path of a shape. [Allotrope]
A component mapping is part of a component strategy and maps a component specification to one or more HDF data sets. [Allotrope]
An granular part of an object aggregate that plays the role of a system. [Allotrope]
A component selection is a specification of a set of values of a single component specification of a data cube. [Allotrope]
A component specification is a part specification about the components of a system. [Allotrope]
A single physical entity inhering in an bearer by virtue of the bearer's quantities or relative ratios of subparts. [PATO]
Examples: calcium composition (which may inhere in bone); haemoglobin composition (which may inhere in blood).

Definition: A collection of one or more atomic types or small arrays of such types. Similar to a struct in C or a common block in Fortran. [Allotrope]
Value representation for compound types. [Allotrope]
A unit for the correction factor used in chromatography for the compressibility of the mobile phase.
Compression is the act of reducing volume by applying a force. [Allotrope]
Examples: In the case of tablets it is the act of forming a solid plug from individual powder / granule components.

Definition: A compression device is a device that is designed to compress to volume of material by applying force. [Allotrope]
A computer is a device that can be instructed to carry out an arbitrary set of arithmetic or logical operations automatically. [Wikipedia]

A computer is a general-purpose device that can be programmed to carry out a set of arithmetic or logical operations automatically. Since a sequence of operations can be readily changed, the computer can solve more than one kind of problem. [Wikipedia]
A concentration that is relatively high. [Allotrope]
A preparative step where the concentration of one component is increased. [CHMO]
A concentration (datum) is a quantification facet that quantifies a quality inhering in a substance by virtue of the amount of the bearer's there is mixed with another substance. [Allotrope]
Concentration is a molecular quality inhering in a substance by virtue of the amount of the bearer's there is mixed with another substance. [PATO]
Source: Green Book, 2nd ed.: IUPAC Quantities, Units and Symbols in Physical Chemistry. Second Edition, Blackwell Scientific Publications, Oxford, 1993.

Definition: An concentration measurement is the determination of the concentration of a compound in solution. [Allotrope]
Examples: simple read, i.e. simple measurement at a defined wavelength; protein concentration measurement; quick slope, linearity measurement, UV measurement in which the cell pathlength is varied. [Allotrope].

Definition: A concentration process profile is a quality process profile that tracks some concentration. [Allotrope]
A concentration profile is a profile that quantifies the concentration of a material entity over time. [Allotrope]

A concentration ratio configuration is a device configuration of a fluid controlling or monitoring device, that controls or monitors the concentration ratio of a mixture at the site of some system component. [Allotrope]

A concentration ratio setting is a setting that specifies some concentration ratio configuration of a fluid controlling or monitoring device, that controls or monitors the concentration ratio of a mixture at the site of some system component. [Allotrope]
A concept datum is a classification datum that classifies a thing by a SKOS concept. [Allotrope]
A condenser lens is a lens with the function to converge a radiation beam to a defined beam size. [Allotrope]
A condenser lens voltage setting is voltage setting specifying the voltage of some condenser lens. [Allotrope]

A condition is an information content entity that is about the portion of reality under which something occurs or is valid. The condition is limited by its scope and may have preconditions. It restricts the possible realizations. [Allotrope]
Condition role is a contextual role of an information object that specifies a prerequisite. [Allotrope]
A physical quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's disposition to transmit of an entity through a medium. [PATO]
Examples: Examples could be heat or electricity or sound.

Definition: Conductometry is the measurement of the conductance of a solution as a function of concentration. Measurements are made indirectly across the resistance of the solution with alternating current. [CHMO]
A specific combination of qualities that the bearer realizes at some time. [Allotrope]
A configuration process profile is a quality process profile that tracks the configuration of a system or device. [Allotrope]
A configuration specification is a situation specification that is about a realized configuration inhered in a specification target. [Allotrope]
A conformance assessment is an assessment about whether two sources of data conform. [Allotrope]
A conglomerate association state is an association state where the primary particles associate as a collection of different types of particle. [Allotrope]
A state s with participating materials  m1 and m2  and m1 is connected to m2. [Allotrope]
Connecting is bringing two or more topological flows into connection. [Allotrope, NIST]
A connecting device is a device that has the function to connect things. [Allotrope]
Consequence is the causal role of an information content entity that is about something causally resultant from another thing. [Allotrope]

PrefLabel: constant flow rate mobile phase delivery
Definition: Constant flow rate mobile phase delivery is a mobile phase delivery process whereby the mobile phase is delivered by maintaining a constant flow rate of the mobile phase. [Allotrope]
Constant pressure mobile phase delivery is a mobile phase delivery process whereby the mobile phase is delivered by maintaining a constant pressure of the mobile phase. [Allotrope]
A constant quality process profile is a quality process profile where the tracked  quality does not change. [Allotrope]
Examples: A solid material has a constant state of matter quality profile when it does not melt or sublimate. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: steady (state); steady quality state; being steady; unchanging (state); being stable; stable (state); unchanging quality state; remaining unchanged; stable quality state
Definition: A constant quality state is a quality state where the quality does not change. [Allotrope]
Examples: being red; being solid

Definition: A process where a essential material entity participant ceases to exist at the end and  it was existing at the start. [Allotrope]
Consuming energy is a consuming that consumes energy. [Allotrope]
Consuming signal is consuming of signals. [Allotrope]
A device that has the function to contain material. [Allotrope]
Examples: box, can, plate, rack; tray, flask, vial

Definition: A container diameter is a diameter of some container. [Allotrope]
A container height is a height of some container. [Allotrope]
A container identifier is an identifier that identifies some container. [Allotrope]
A container shape is a classification datum that classifies the shape of some container. [Allotrope]
Container state description is a state facet that describes the state of the container used in the measurement run. [Allotrope]
ScopeNote: The container's material is not a container state. [Allotrope]
Examples: A container state can be opened or closed. [Allotrope]

Definition: Container type is a classification datum that classifies the type of container used. [Allotrope]
Containing is the state of keeping an object in the inside of a cavity. [Allotrope]
The state of keeping a flow within spatial limits. [Allotrope]
Examples: A vacuum bag contains debris vacuumed from a house. [NIST]

Definition: A content specification is a part specification that specifies a contained portion of material of a container. [Allotrope]
A contextual role is a representation of a specific interpretation of the information content object or of the circumstances that the information content object is referencing to. [Allotrope]
Examples: result of a measurement; objective of a specification; parameter of a calculation

Definition: A continuant is an entity that persists, endures, or continues to exist through time while maintaining its identity. [BFO]
B is a continuant fiat boundary if b is an immaterial entity that is of zero, one or two dimensions and does not include a spatial region as part. [BFO]

AltLabels: continuous phase; continuous medium role; continuous medium
Definition:
The continuous phase role is the dispersion role of a portion of material constituting the medium, a phase that exhibits continuity throughout the
dispersion. [NIST]
A contributor is a role of a person in an audit trail. The contributor gave some content to the electronic record. [Allotrope]
A control command is an action specification that specifies a setting to be set by a controlling process. [Allotrope]
A control profile setting is a profile setting that specifies how a system's configuration is controlled over time. [Allotrope]
A control sample role is a sample role of a material that does contain a known amount of analyte for control purposes. [Allotrope]
A control setting is a setting that controls how a process is executed by some system. [Allotrope]
A controlled lab reactor is a reactor that maintains temperature and other reaction parameters and has measuring devices. [Allotrope]
ScopeNote: In chemistry, a Controlled Lab Reactor or CLR is any reaction system where there is an element of automated control. Generally these devices refers to a jacketed glass vessel where a circulating chiller unit pumps a thermal control fluid through the jacket to accurately control the temperature of the vessel contents. Additional to this, it is common to have a series of sensors (temperature, pH, pressure) measuring and recording parameters about the reactor contents. It is additionally possible to control pumps to act on the reactor. [Wikipedia]

AltLabels: controlled object; control target; control target role
Definition: Controlled object is the role of a material entity that is being controlled by a controller in a controlling process. [Allotrope]
A device that has the function to control some quality or process. [Allotrope]
A controller configuration is a device configuration of a controller, that directly influences the controlling process done by the controller towards a goal. [Allotrope]
Controller role is a controlling role of some material entity that is controlling some other object or a process. [Allotrope]
Controlling is changing or regulating a flow in its magnitude. [NIST, Allotrope]
A role of a participant in a controlling process. [Allotrope]
Conversion is a reaction composition quality dependent on the fraction of reactant remaining. [Allotrope]
A conversion device is a device that has the function to convert something. [Allotrope]

A plot of a quantity related to the absorption, for example absorbance or cross section, multiplied by the quantum yield for the process considered against a measure of photon energy such as frequency, wavenumber or wavelength. [CHMO]
Converting is a process that changes from one form of a flow (material, energy, signal) to another. [NIST]
Changing from one form of a flow energy to another. [NIST]
Examples: A motor converts energy into mechanical energy.

Definition: Changing from one form of a flow material to another. [NIST]

AltLabels: coolant; heat transfer fluid; cooling medium
Definition: A role of a material that acts as a heat sink as it undergoes a phase change. [Allotrope]
The transfer of thermal energy from a material to its surrounding environment. [CHMO]
A kind of heat exchanger or radiator designed to remove excess heat. [Wikipedia]
A changing role is a role realized in some cooling process. [Allotrope]
A coordinate is a scalar as component of a vector or tuple in a coordinate system specifying a point in space. [Allotrope]
Index coordinate of a point in multi-dimensional array. [Allotrope]
A coordinate role is a contextual role of a scalar as component of a vector or tuple in a coordinate system specifying a point in space. [Allotrope]
A corrected peak area is a peak area corrected for some relative response factor. [Allotrope]
A correlation coefficient is a numerical measure of some type of correlation, meaning a statistical relationship between two variables. [Wikipedia]
Any piece of apparatus used to measure electric charge. [CHMO]

Coulometric titration is the process of determining the quantity of a sample by adding measured increments of a titrant until the end-point, at which essentially all of the sample has reacted, is reached. In a coulometric titration the titrant is generated electrochemically by passing a constant current through an electrolyte. [CHMO]
An electrochemical technique where the total Coulombs of electricity required to complete (fully oxidize or fully reduce the sample in) an electrochemical reaction is measured. [CHMO]
A datum that has non-negative integer values that is about the number of discrete things. [Allotrope]

The count fraction (datum) is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the fraction pertaining the number of object of a constituent divided by the total number of objects of all constituents in the object aggregate. [Allotrope]
ScopeNote: Definition is generalized to cover any count fraction, but usually it applies to particles in a mixture. [Allotrope]

Definition: The count fraction is a quality pertaining the number of particles of a constituent divided by the total number of particles of all constituents in the mixture. [Allotrope]
A country name is a location facet that denotes a country. [Allotrope]
Counts are like ratio scale that they have a zero point but there are no meaningful fractional units. [Allotrope]
Coupling is connecting together material such that the members are still distinguishable from each other. [NIST]
A device that has the function to couple things. [Allotrope]
Covered state is a connected state where something is located on the surface of another thing and prevents some kind of material or energy flow through that surface. [Allotrope]
Covering is a joining process where the joining is on to the surface in such way that it is preventing some kind of material or energy flow through that surface. [Allotrope]
A covering device is a device that has the function to cover something. [Allotrope]
A creation time is the time when an entity was created. [Allotrope]
A creator is a role of a person in an audit trail. The creator generated the electronic record. [Allotrope]
An instrument setting indicating at what temperature the control system should engage a cryogenic coolant for cooling. [Allotrope]
An interpolation algorithm using cubic polynomials. [Allotrope]
A cumulative count (datum) is a count that has non-negative integer values that is about the cumulative number of discrete things. [Allotrope]
A cumulative distribution percentage is a statistical facet that describes the percentage of population members meeting a given condition. [Allotrope]
A cumulative particle density is a scalar quantity datum that quantifies the number density of particles meeting a given criterion. [Allotrope]
A cumulative particle density is the number density of particles meeting a given criterion. [Allotrope]
A cup is a container with a cylindrical shape and no top surface. [Allotrope]
A cup radius is a radius that quantifies the radius of some cup. [Allotrope]
A curator is a role of a person in an audit trail, who curates the electronic record. [Allotrope]

A current configuration is a device configuration of a current controlling or monitoring device, that controls or monitors the target electric current at the site of some system component. [Allotrope]

A current setting is a setting that specifies some current configuration of a current controlling or monitoring device, that controls or monitors the target electric current at the site of some system component. [Allotrope]

Curve fitting is a data transformation that is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints. [Wikipedia]
A custom information aggregate document is a document that aggregates custom information documents. [Allotrope]
A custom information document is a document that about some labeled information entity for which limited meaning and/or context is known. [Allotrope]
Examples: Information placed by a user in acquisition or processing software in a field that is ambiguously defined by the software ( e.g. ‘SPARE FIELD 1’). This allows the information tag and value to be unambiguously linked and therefore retrieved by those with knowledge into its use for the data being interrogated. [Allotrope]

Definition: A cycle count is a count of the number of iterations of a repeated process. [Allotrope]
A cycle threshold result is an qPCR assay result that records the cycle at which the threshold was passed. [Allotrope]
A cycle threshold value setting is a setting that sets the threshold value used for automatic qPCR cycle threshold determination. [Allotrope]
A cyclic rate profile is a rate profile of a process that follows a cyclic pattern. [Allotrope]
A cyclic scale is a type of measurement scale that classifies values based on recurring intervals. [Allotrope]
Examples: angle; weekday; orientation

Definition: Quality of a material entity of cylindrical or tubular shape which describes its length along its main (non-circular) dimension. [Allotrope]
A damper is an inhibition device that deadens, restrains, or depresses. [Wikipedia]
Dark background correction enabled is a setting for a Raman detector that controls whether compensation for background signals without illumination is active. [Allotrope]

Data acquisition is the process of sampling signals that measure real world physical conditions and converting the resulting samples into digital numeric values that can be manipulated by a computer. [Wikipedia]
A device to acquire signals or data. [Allotrope]
Data aggregation is a data reduction that applies an aggregating function on the data to produce an aggregated (summary) datum from a collection of data items. [Allotrope]
Examples: averaging; totaling a sum

Definition: A term used meaning the processing and manipulation of the spectral data produced for the purposes of improving spectral appearance, change the signal to noise ratio (S/N), or resolution. The term is often collectively used in conjunction with line broadening, sharpening, averaging, smoothing. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: data aggregation; collecting data; aggregating data
Definition: A data transformation that assigns some data to a collection. [Allotrope]
Represents a collection of observations, possibly organized into various slices, conforming to some common dimensional structure. [QB]
A data cube identifier is an identifier for a data cube. A data cube is a multi-dimensional dataset conforming to the W3C DataCube specification (https://www.w3.org/TR/vocab-data-cube/). [Allotrope]
A description of distribution of a quantity with respect to a set of parameters. [Allotrope]
Data extraction is a data transformation process whereby specific data is taken out of a larger set of data and presented in a usable format. [Allotrope]
A data flow specification is a flow specification about how information is exchanged between processes. [Allotrope]
A data format conversion software is a software the converts data into a specified target format. [Allotrope]
A data format specification is the information content borne by the document published defining the specification. [IAO]
Examples: The ISO document specifying what encompasses an XML document; The instructions in a XSD file [IAO]

Definition: A data format specification type is a classification datum that classifies the data format used to store data. [Allotrope]
Examples: Centroid or profile data in mass spectometry

Definition: Data input role is a type of contextual role of an information artifact that is the input of a process. [Allotrope]
Data output role is a type of contextual role of an information artifact that is the output of a process. [Allotrope]
A data point is the single point in a coordinate space. [Allotrope]
A data processing aggregate document is a document that aggregates data processing documents. [Allotrope]
A data processing description is a description of some data processing operation. [Allotrope]
A data processing document is a document that encompasses the metadata associated with a data processing operation. [Allotrope]
A data processing method is a plan specification that specifies how data processing process is to be executed. [Allotrope]
A data processing omission setting is a data processing setting that marks whether the related dataset should be excluded from some data processing. [Allotrope]
A data processing setting is a setting that controls how a data processing process is executed by some system. [Allotrope]
Data processing time is the time when a data processing starts. [Allotrope]
A data processing type is a classification datum that classifies the type of data processing performed. [Allotrope]
Data reduction is the transformation of numerical or alphabetical digital information derived empirically or experimentally into a corrected, ordered, and/or simplified form. [Wikipedia]

A data region describes a part of a data distribution function at a definite range of the experimental parameter (independent variable) of the distribution function. This definition includes a single data point of the distribution function. [Allotrope]
A data region aggregate aggregate document is a document that aggregates data region documents. [Allotrope]
A data region area is a data region facet that quantitates the area enclosed by a data region and the selected baseline. [Allotrope]
A data region document is a document that encompasses the information associated with a data region. [Allotrope]
A data region end is a data region facet that denotes the last value of the abscissa that belongs to the region. [Allotrope]
A data region end point is the data point of the region with the largest abscissa value. [Allotrope]
A data region facet is a facet that is part of a data region. [Allotrope]
A data region identifier is an identifier that identifies some data region. [Allotrope]
A data region name is a written name that denotes some data region. [Allotrope]
A data region point is a data point that is a member of a data region. [Allotrope]
A data region start is a data region facet that denotes the first value of the abscissa that belongs to the region. [Allotrope]
A data region start point is the data point of the region with the smallest abscissa value. [Allotrope]
A data region value at end is a data region facet that denotes the last value of the ordinate that belongs to the region. [Allotrope]
A data region value at start is a data region facet that denotes the first value of the ordinate that belongs to the region. [Allotrope]
A data selection is a n-dimensional subset of data of a data cube. The selection can be based on the dimensions or on the measures. [Allotrope]
A data shuffling algorithm setting is a data processing setting specifying the algorithm used to process phase sensitive two-dimensional spectra. [Allotrope]
A data source aggregate document is a document that aggregates data source documents. [Allotrope]
A data source document is a document that encompasses the information associated with some data with the role of data input. [Allotrope]
A data source feature is a facet that defines the feature with the role of a description or classification of a property, characteristic or facet of some data with the role of data input. [Allotrope]
A data source identifier is an identifier that identifies some data with the role of data input. [Allotrope]

A data stream represents the bitstream of data flowing from source to target. The data stream may include data conversion if datatypes of source and target differ, and may include transformations like compression or encryption. Source and targets are hyperslabs on datasets. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: information technology system; IT system; cyber-physical system
Definition: A data system is an artificial  system of physical devices and software running on it designed to process information or control. [Allotrope]
A data system document is a document that encapsulates the information associated with some data system. [Allotrope]
A data system instance identifier is an identifier that identifies an instance of some data system. [Allotrope]
A converting process that converts the signals from one form into another by changing its content. [Allotrope]

A data type mapping describes how data types defined in RDF are mapped to HDF data types. RDF data types include XSD data types such as xsd:integer or xsd:double, rdf:Resource and also complex (and possibly nested) data types defined by shapes. [Allotrope]
A data update is a description of individual data changes within an electronic record, that cannot be otherwise described by a remove / add combination. [Allotrope]
A data validity is a qualification about the suitability of some data for a specified purpose. [Allotrope]
A data validity assessment is an assessment about the validity of some data for a specified purpose. [Allotrope]
A data validity code is an code that indicates the validity of some data. [Allotrope]

A database is an organized collection of data, generally stored and accessed electronically from a computer system. Where databases are more complex they are often developed using formal design and modeling techniques. [Wikipedia]
A database primary key is an identifier of a database record. [Allotrope]
A database record is an electronic record that is stored in a database. [Allotrope]
A multi-dimensional array of data elements, together with supporting metadata. [Allotrope]

A dataset dataspace describes the dimensionality of the dataset. The dimensions of a dataset can be fixed (unchanging), or they may be unlimited, which means that they are extendible (i.e. they can grow larger). [Allotrope]

An object that describes the storage format of the individual data points in a data set. There are two categories of datatypes: atomic and compound datatypes. An atomic type is a type which cannot be decomposed into smaller units at the API level. A compound datatype is a collection of one or more atomic types or small arrays of such types. [Allotrope]

A label is a symbol that is part of some other datum and is used to either partially define  the denotation of that datum or to provide a means for identifying the datum as a member of the set of data with the same label [IAO]
A viability quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the cessation of the bearer's life. [PATO]
Dead cell count is a cell counter result data that states the number of dead cells that were counted in the cell counting assay. [Allotrope]
Dead cell count is the cell count of the partition of dead cells. [Allotrope]
Dead cell density is a cell counter result data that quantifies the number density of the dead cells in the sample in the cell counting assay. [Allotrope]
Dead cell density is the cell density of the partition of dead cells. [Allotrope]
Debris is a role of material to be waste. [Allotrope]
Deciding is making a choice from a set of alternatives. [Allotrope]
A decision is a proposition that is a choice made from a set of alternative propositions. [Allotrope]
An decreasing quality process profile is a quality process profile where the tracked determinate quality is continuously decreasing in magnitude. [Allotrope]
Decrementing is reducing the magnitude of a quality in a predetermined and fixed manner. [Allotrope]
Dedusting is the process of removal of dust. [Allotrope]
A default condition is a condition that is member of a set of conditions that is always true if all others conditions in the collections are false. [Allotrope]
ScopeNote: There must be no more than one default condition in any collection of conditions.
Examples: A default value in a conditional parameter specification. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: fallback; default role; default; fallback condition; fallback condition role; default condition; fallback role
Definition: A default condition role is the condition role of an item in a collection of information content entities that applies (is true) if no other items apply (are false). [Allotrope]
A default role is a directive purpose that assigns a specification to be applied to a context if no other specification is asserted in that context. [Allotrope]
An default transition is a successor role in the scope of an exclusive gateway that specifies the succeeding activity if no guard conditions on the gateway are met. [Allotrope]
Defining purpose is the contextual role of some information that has the purpose to define an entity. [Allotrope]
A definition is a proposition that succinctly characterizes an entity. [Allotrope]
A deflection, in physics, refers to the change in an objects' acceleration as a consequence of contact (collision) with a surface or the influence of a field. [Wikipedia]
A degassed sample weight is the sample weight of a sample after it has gone through a degassing process. [Allotrope]
A degasser is a device to remove gasses from a fluid which could otherwise form bubbles. [Wikipedia]
Degassing is a sample preparation process whereby the adsorbed (dissolved) gas is removed from a solid or liquid. [Allotrope]

Degradation is the state of changing in the qualities of a material under the influence of one or more environmental factors such as heat, light or chemicals such as acids, alkalies and some salts to a lower level of quality. [Allotrope]

A degradation product is an impurity resulting from a chemical change in the drug substance brought about during manufacture and/or storage of the new drug product by the effect of, for example, light, temperature, pH, water, or by reaction with an excipient and/or the immediate container closure system. [ICH-Q3B]
A delay is a process property that describes a difference in time between a process boundary and some other point in time. [Allotrope]
A delay time setting (hot tack) is a control setting that specifies the duration between opening of the grips and removal of the sample. [Allotrope]
Delivering material is the importing of material to a location or site. [Allotrope]

Denaturing is the process of partial or total alteration of the native structure of a macromolecule resulting from the loss of tertiary or tertiary and secondary structure that is a consequence of the disruption of stabilizing weak bonds. [IUPAC]
Source: IUPAC. Compendium of Chemical Terminology, 2nd ed. (the "Gold Book"). Compiled by A. D. McNaught and A. Wilkinson. Blackwell Scientific Publications, Oxford (1997).

Definition: A denaturing duration setting is a duration setting that specifies the intended duration of some denaturing process. [Allotrope]
A denaturing temperature setting is a temperature setting that specifies the intended temperature of some denaturing process. [Allotrope]
Denominator is the conceptual role of a scalar that indicates the number of equal parts into which the unit is divided. [Allotrope]
Denoting is a process that assigns a symbol to an entity in order to reference it. [Allotrope]
The measurement of the density of a sample. [CHMO]

A density of theoretical plates (chromatography) is a chromatography peak facet that measures the amount of band broadening normalized per length unit that occurs during the separation and thus the efficiency of the chromatographic system. [Allotrope]
Departure is the achievement of leaving the source site in a moving process. [Allotrope]
A dependent variable is a contextual role of an information artifact that represents the outputs or outcomes whose variation is being studied. [Wikipedia]
A 1-D extent quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's downward or backward or inward dimenision. [PATO]
A derivation record dataset is an audit record dataset that contains the metadata and data that is needed to record derivations on an electronic record in an activity. [Allotrope]
A derived electropherogram is derived from the outcome of an electrophoresis run and reports the response of the detector as a function of a derived unit. [Allotrope]
A derived electropherogram data cube is a data cube that represents a derived electropherogram. [Allotrope]
A derived measure is a measure that is the outcome of some indirect measurement. The derived value is derived from base measures by calculations following a formula or algorithm. [Allotrope]
Describing is a process by which an account of some relevant characteristics, qualities or events of an entity are given or presented. [Allotrope]
A description is a proposition about an existing entity. [Allotrope]
A role of an information content entity that is meant to describe an object. [Allotrope]
A descriptive statistic is a summary statistic that quantitatively describes or summarizes features of a collection of information. [Wikipedia]

Descriptive statistics is the process of using and analyzing descriptive statistics. A descriptive statistic is a summary statistic that quantitatively describes or summarizes features of a collection of information. [Wikipedia]
A designative purpose is a type of contextual role of information artifacts that denote an entity in order to describe its characteristics. [Allotrope]
Destination is the contextual role of an information object that is about the spatio-temporal location at the end of a process that changes it. [Allotrope]
Destination role is the localization role of a site where the localized object is at the end of the localization process. [Allotrope]
Detecting is observing the presence of an entity. This occurs when a threshold value of a quantity (quality, disposition, process property) is exceeded. [Allotrope]
A detecting state is a state that occurs when a detector detects its detection target. [Allotrope]
Detection bandwidth is a device setting of a detector controlling the bandwidth of the detection wavelength. [Allotrope]
A detection duration setting is a setting specifies the total duration of a detection process. [Allotrope]
The role of a participant in a detecting process. [Allotrope]
A role inhered when the presence of the bearer indicates the presence of the detection target in a detection process. [Allotrope]
The role inhered by being the objective of a detecting activity. [Allotrope]
A detection type is a classification datum that classifies the type of detection performed by the detector.. [Allotrope]
A detection wavelength quality is a device setting which determines the wavelength range that a detector of electromagnetic radiation detects. [Allotrope]
Any piece of apparatus used to detect an analyte. [CHMO]
A detector bandwidth setting is a control setting that specifies the bandwidth of a particular signal to be measured by the detector. [Allotrope]
A detector carriage speed setting is a control setting that specifies the speed of a detector carriage. [Allotrope]
A detector configuration is a device configuration of a detector. [Allotrope]
A detector control aggregate document is a document that aggregates detector control documents. [Allotrope]
A detector control document is a document that encompasses the information associated with control of a detector. [Allotrope]
A detector distance setting is the distance between the ultrasonic sensor of the foam qualification device and the bottom of a test container during a baseline measurement. [Allotrope]
A detector distance setting is a control setting that specifies the distance between the detector and the scanned plate. [Allotrope]
The detector gain is a (relative) amount by which a detector to increases the magnitude of a signal from the input to the output port by adding energy to the signal. [Allotrope]
A detector gain setting is setting that specifies the gain of the detector. [Allotrope]
A detector identifier is a measurement device identifier that identifies some detector. [Allotrope]
A detector model number is a model number that denotes some class of detectors. [Allotrope]
A detector offset setting is a detector setting parameter that adds the specified value to its output signal.  It is often used to avoid negative signal values. [Allotrope]
A detector relative offset setting is a detector setting that specifies the offset of the signals of two detectors to align them along the x-axis. [Allotrope]
The detector role is a detection role of a material entity that is detecting some other entity. [Allotrope]

Definition: A detector sampling rate setting is a detector setting parameter that specifies the rate at which the detector changes its output signal.  It is limited by the actual physical/chemical process of detection and the detector electronics.  Often the sample rate is set lower than the maximum sampling rate so that adjacent data points can be averaged to provide better signal to noise. [Allotrope]
A detector scan range setting is a detector setting that sets the wavelength range of scans as well as the increment between different scans. [Allotrope]
Examples: A scan range from 280 to 700 nm with an increment of 2 nm from one scan to the next.

AltLabels: detector scan rate; detection scan rate
Definition: A detector setting that sets the frequency of scans per time unit. [Allotrope]
A detector setting is a setting that specifies a detector configuration. [Allotrope]
A detector signal is a signal that is produced by a detector that signals the presence or magnitude of the entity observed by the detector. [Allotrope]
A detector type is a classification datum that describes the detector type. [Allotrope]
A detector view volume is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the volume of material visible to the detector at the point of measurement. [Allotrope]
A detector wavelength setting is a control setting that specifies the wavelength of a particular signal to be measured by the detector. [Allotrope]
A surfactant (or a mixture containing one or more surfactants) disposed to having cleaning properties in dilute solutions. [ChEBI]
A detergent role is a cleaning role of a surface active agent (or a mixture containing one of more surface active agents) having cleaning properties in dilute solution. [IUPAC]
Source: PAC, 1972, 31, 577 (Manual of Symbols and Terminology for Physicochemical Quantities and Units, Appendix II: Definitions, Terminology and Symbols in Colloid and Surface Chemistry) on page 612

Definition: A deuterium lamp is a low-pressure gas-discharge light source that emits light with a continuous spectrum mainly in the ultraviolet region. [Wikipedia]
A deviation is a quantification facet that quantifies the absolute or relative difference of an observed value from another value. [Allotrope]
A device is an artifact that is designed to perform a function primarily by means of its mechanical or electrical nature. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: instrument acquisition method; device method; instrument method; acquisition method
Definition: A device acquisition method is a machine readable plan specification that specifies how the acquisition software of an instrument is to execute the instrument's portion of an analysis. [Allotrope]
A device control aggregate document is a document that aggregates device control documents. [Allotrope]
A device control document is a document that encompasses the information associated with control of a device. [Allotrope]
A device document is a document that encompasses the information associated with a device. [Allotrope]

A device method is a plan specification that specifies how some process is to be executed on a device. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: instrument id; instrument method identifier; device id
Definition: A device method identifier is an identifier that identifies the device method used in a process. [Allotrope]
A device process is a planned process that realizes a function by a device or device system. [Allotrope]

Definition: A site that is related to a device. [Allotrope]

An artificial system that is mainly composed of devices. [Allotrope]

A diagnostic trace is a data distribution function that records the output of some diagnostic monitoring process over time. [Allotrope]

A figure that expresses one or more propositions. [IAO]
Examples: A molecular structure ribbon cartoon showing helices, turns and sheets and their relations to each other in space.

Definition: Diameter is a length which is equal to the length of any straight line segment that passes through the center of a circle and whose endpoints are on the circular boundary. [PATO]
A length quality which is equal to the length of any straight line segment that passes through the center of a circle and whose endpoints are on the circular boundary. [PATO]
The absolute value of the mole fraction for one diastereomer in a mixture minus the mole fraction for the other. [CHMO]
The ratio of the percentage of one diastereomer in a mixture to that of the other. [CHMO]
A BidiMap is a data structure that allows a bidirectional lookup a value by a key. [Allotrope]
The electric displacement vector and the product of the electric field strength with the permittivity of vacuum. [IUPAC]

Dielectric polarization is the quality inhered in a dielectric that is the difference between the electric displacement vector and the product of the electric field strength with the permittivity of vacuum. [IUPAC]
Source: IUPAC. Compendium of Chemical Terminology, 2nd ed. (the "Gold Book"). Compiled by A. D. McNaught and A. Wilkinson. Blackwell Scientific Publications, Oxford (1997).
