Reaction selectivity is a reaction composition that is expressed as the number of moles of desired product per the number of moles of undesired product. [Wikipedia]
A reaction selectivity disposition is a disposition of a reaction mixture to have a reaction selectivity. [Allotrope]
A reaction temperature data cube is a data cube that represents the reaction temperature over time. [Allotrope]
A reaction temperature profile is a profile that quantifies the temperature of the reaction solution over time in a synthesis. [Allotrope]
A reactor is a container for controlling a biological or chemical reaction or process. [Allotrope]
A reactor jacket is a jacket that controls the temperature of a reactor. [Allotrope]
A read is a process boundary within a measuring where a data about the measured object is captured. [Allotrope]
Examples: A read at regular time intervals during the measurement of a process profile. [Allotrope]; Multiple reads for statistics and error corrections. [Allotrope]

Definition: A read interval setting is a control setting that specifies the duration between individual reads in a measurement. [Allotrope]

A role inhering in a biological or chemical entity that is intended to be applied in a scientific technique to participate (or have molecular components that participate) in a chemical reaction that facilitates the generation of data about some entity distinct from the bearer, or the generation of some specified material output distinct from the bearer. [OBI]

AltLabels: reagent role; chemical ionization reagent gas
Definition: Reagent role is the role of a gas that reacts with ions to produce product ions through ion/molecule reactions; for example, a gas such as methane, ammonia, or isobutane used in chemical ionization to create reagent ions or a gas used in ion traps or collision cells to perform gas-phase ion/molecule reactions. [IUPAC]
Source: K. K. Murray, R. K. Boyd, M. N. Eberlin, G. J. Langley, L. Li and Y. Naito, Pure Appl. Chem., 2013, 85, 1515-1609

Definition: A real Fourier transform enabled setting is a data processing setting specifying that a real Fourier Transform is executed as opposed to the conventional Discreet Fourier Transform. [Allotrope]
A factor with a real number as value. [Allotrope]

To say that b is a realizable entity is to say that b is a specifically dependent continuant that inheres in some independent continuant which is not a spatial region and is of a type instances of which are realized in processes of a correlated type.´[BFO]
Examples: the role of this boundary to delineate where Utah and Colorado meet; the disposition of this piece of metal to conduct electricity.; the function of your reproductive organs; the role of being a doctor; the disposition of your blood to coagulate

Definition: The reason of a change or an signature to an electronic record. [Allotrope]
Sent object is the role of a transferred object at the start of the transferring process. [Allotrope]
The role inhered in a material entity that receives the transferred object in a transfer process. [Allotrope]
A process that transports a signal across a system boundary into the system. [Allotrope]
The accomplishment that a transferred signal reaches at its designated target. [Allotrope]
The process of copying the information in a signal into a persistent information bearer. [Allotrope]
A reference is an information content entity that is referred to in another information content entity for the purpose of comparison. [Allotrope]
Examples: reference data used to compare to with experimental data

Definition: A reference DNA control sample role is a sample role of a material that contains a known reference DNA sequence. [Allotrope]
A reference DNA copy number is a PCR result specifying the DNA copy number of a reference gene or endogenous control within a PCR experiment. [Allotrope]
A reference DNA description is a description that describes the DNA target of a reference gene or endogenous control within the PCR experiment. [Allotrope]

A reference datum is the contextual role of some information content entity that is referenced in the context of another information content entity for the purpose of comparison. It describes or denotes an object that has the role of a reference role. [Allotrope]
A reference identifier is an identifier that identifies some reference data that is being used as a comparator. [Allotrope]
A reference material document is a document that encompasses the information associated with the reference material in an analysis. [Allotrope]
A reference material is an identifier that identifies some material with the role of reference material. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: calibration material role; standard material role; standard; reference material; standard material; calibration material
Definition: A reference material role is the role of a material used in a calibration whose qualities are sufficiently homogenous and well established to be used as reference. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: calibration material role; standard material role; standard; reference material; standard material; calibration material
Definition: A reference material role is the role of a material used in a calibration whose qualities are sufficiently homogenous and well established to be used as reference. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: calibration material role; standard material role; standard; reference material; standard material; calibration material
Definition: A reference material role is the role of a material used in a calibration whose qualities are sufficiently homogenous and well established to be used as reference. [Allotrope]
A reference material weight is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the mass of a material with the role of reference material in the analysis. [Allotrope]
A reference pan role is the role of the measurement pan realized in a DSC measurement that is without sample content. [Allotrope]
A role inhered by a participant that is a reference for qualitative or quantitative comparison in relation to other entities. [Allotrope]
Examples: measuring standard

Definition: A reference sample description is a description that describes some material with the role of reference sample. [Allotrope]
An reference sample role is a sample role of a material that does contain a known amount of analyte. [Allotrope]
Reference signal is the role of a signal that relates to another signal as reference for comparison. [Allotrope]
Referencing is the process of mentioning or referring to an entity by using a denotation of the entity. [Allotrope]
A reflectance is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the fraction of incident radiation reflected by a surface or discontinuity. [IUPAC]
Reflectance is an optical quality that is the fraction of incident radiation reflected by a surface or discontinuity. [IUPAC]
Source: PAC, 2007, 79, 293 (Glossary of terms used in photochemistry, 3rd edition (IUPAC Recommendations 2006))

Definition: A reflectance spectrum is a spectrum that plots the reflectance of radiance as the function of frequency or wavelength. [Allotrope]
A reflectance spectrum data cube is a data cube that represents a reflectance spectrum. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: reflectance ultra-violet-visible spectrometry; reflection UV-VIS spectrometry; reflectance ultraviolet-visible spectroscopy; reflection UV/VIS spectrometry; reflection ultraviolet-visible spectroscopy; reflection ultra-violet-visible spectrometry; reflectance ultra-violet-visible spectrophotometry; reflection UV-VIS spectroscopy; reflection ultraviolet-visible spectrometry; reflectance UV-VIS spectrometry; reflection ultra-violet-visible spectroscopy; reflectance UV/VIS spectrometry; reflection UV/VIS spectroscopy; reflectance UV-VIS spectroscopy; reflectance UV/VIS spectroscopy; reflectance ultra-violet-visible spectroscopy
Definition: Ultraviolet-visible spectroscopy where the reflection or scattering of radiation from the sample surface is detected. [CHMO]
Reflection is the change in direction of a wavefront at an interface between two different media so that the wavefront returns into the medium from which it originated. [Wikipedia]
Any method for determining structure by directing a beam of particles or X-rays onto an extremely flat surface and measuring the intensity of the reflected radiation as a function of angle. [CHMO]

AltLabels: index of refraction; refraction index; refractive index (datum)
Definition: Refraction index is a quality quantification facet, that quantifies how fast light travels through a material. It is defined as n = c/v, where c is the speed of light in vacuum and v is the phase velocity of light in the medium. [Wikipedia]
The refractive index is an optical quality inhered in a material by virtue of how fast light travels through the material. [Allotrope]

A piece of apparatus, consisting of a light source, a hollow prism and a photoelectric cell that is used to detect non-ultraviolet-absorbing molecules in a sample separated by chromatography. Light from the sample passes through a flow cell with two channels towards the photoelectric cell. One channel holds the eluent from the column, whereas the other holds a control sample (solvent that has not passed through the column).  Detection occurs when the light is bent due to molecules eluting from the column, and this is read as a disparity between the two channels. [CHMO]

AltLabels: refractive index detection; RI detection; RID; refractive index measuring
Definition: A refractive index measurement is a measuring based on the change in refractive index of a solution. Light is passed through a hollow prism and focused on a photocell. When a liquid containing the sample is allowed to flow through the prism, the light diverges from its original path and the change in intensity and angle of the transmitted light is measured. [CHMO]
An abstraction for dimensionless refractive index measurements.
A region name is a location facet that denotes a geographic region (state, province). [Allotrope]
A registry is information content entity that is an aggregate of designations. [Allotrope]
Regulating is the adjusting of a flow in response to a control signal. [NIST]
Examples: Turning the valves regulates the flow rate of the liquid flowing from a faucet. [NIST]

Definition: Regulating material is adjusting a quality of material in response to a control signal. [Allotrope]
Examples: regulating the temperature

Definition: A relation role is a contextual role of an information content entity that is about a relation of the subject of the information content entity to another entity. [Allotrope]
B is a relational quality if for some independent continuants c, d and for some time t: b is quality of c at t and b is quality of d at t. [BFO]
Examples: an obligation between one person and another [BFO]; an instance of love [BFO]; a marriage bond [BFO]; a marriage bond, an instance of love, an obligation between one person and another.; John’s role of husband to Mary is dependent on Mary’s role of wife to John, and both are dependent on the object aggregate comprising John and Mary as member parts joined together through the relational quality of being married.

Definition: A relative abundance is a quality quantification facet quantifying the relative number of atoms of a particular isotope in a mixture of the isotope of an element, expressed as a fraction of all the atoms of the element. [Allotrope]
A relative corrected peak area is a relative peak area that denotes the corrected area of the peak relative to some other peak or summation of peaks. . [Allotrope]
A relative data region area is a data region facet that denotes the area of the data region relative to some other region or summation of regions. [Allotrope]

A relative datum role is the contextual role of a datum that is about a quantity or number that is the result of a ratio or difference calculation or an assertion of magnitude relative to a reference entity. [Allotrope]

Relative humidity is the ratio, often expressed as a percentage, of the partial pressure of water in the atmosphere at some observed temperature, to the saturation vapor pressure of pure water at this temperature. [IUPAC]
Source: IUPAC. Compendium of Chemical Terminology, 2nd ed. (the "Gold Book"). Compiled by A. D. McNaught and A. Wilkinson. Blackwell Scientific Publications, Oxford (1997).

AltLabels: relative intensity (datum); relative signal intensity; relative response function
Definition: Relative intensity (datum) is a quantity facet that quantifies the relative magnitude of a signal. [Allotrope]
A relative location is a location facet that denotes a location of an entity relative to some other entity. [Allotrope]
A peak facet that denotes the amount of analyte ascribed to a  the peak relative to the amount of some other analyte or summation of analytes. [Allotrope]
A peak facet that denotes the area of the peak relative to some other peak or summation of peaks. [Allotrope]
A peak facet that denotes the height of the peak relative to some other peak or summation of peaks. [Allotrope]
A relative permittivity result is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the the ability of a medium composed of molecules of a given type to transmit an electric field. [CHEMINF]
Relative permittivity is an electrical and magnetic quality inhered in a medium that is the ratio of the electric field strength in vacuum to that in the medium. [IUPAC]
A relative pressure is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the pressure of a pure substance in a chamber relative to its saturation pressure. [Allotrope]
A relative response is a ratio quantification facet that quantifies the ratio of an analytes device response signal to the device response signal of some reference material. [Allotrope]
A relative response is the ratio of an analytes device response signal to the device response signal of some reference material. [Allotrope]

The relative retention calculation is a process of performing the mathematical ratio quantification of the time a substance and a standard that remain in the stationary phase of a chromatography process. [Allotrope]
A chromatography peak facet that denotes the retention time of the peak relative to some other specified reference peak. [Allotrope]
Relative retention time is a ratio quality of the adjusted or net retention time of a component relative to that of a standard, obtained under identical conditions. [Allotrope]
Source: Orange Book: IUPAC Compendium of Analytical Nomenclature. Second Edition, Blackwell Scientific Publications, Oxford, 1987.

Definition: Relative retention time is a ratio quality of the adjusted or net retention time of a component relative to that of a standard, obtained under identical conditions. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: relative standard curve experiment; relative standard curve
Definition: A relative standard curve qPCR experiment is an experiment using qPCR that measures relative quantity by comparison of diluted samples and known target DNA. [Allotrope]
The relative standard deviation is a ratio of the standard deviation to the arithmetic mean. [Allotrope]
Relative standard deviation role is a statistical datum role of a datum that is a standardized measure of dispersion of a probability distribution or frequency distribution. [Wikipedia]
A relative weight loss on drying is a mass fraction that quantifies the relative value of moisture content lost from a material after a drying process. [Allotrope]

A relaxation delay setting is a nuclear magnetic resonance setting that specifies the duration of time the NMR allocates for the nuclei spin states to return to their original state after being exposed to the radio pulse. [Allotrope]
Taking away a part of a flow from its prefixed place. [NIST]
Removing data is a data transformation that removes parts from an aggregate of data. [Allotrope]
A spatial process of removing a material from a site. [Allotrope]
A single step that can be repeated multiple times during a procedure. [Allotrope]
Examples: A single data acquisition that is repeated multiple times with the same settings during a data acquisition profile.

Definition: A repeated action role is a contextual role of an action specification that specifies the repeated action in a repeated action specification. [Allotrope]
An repeated action specification is an action specification that specifies a repeated activity. [Allotrope]
A repeated process is a composite process that has occurrent parts of subprocesses following the same plan. [Allotrope]
A spatial change processing the increases the spatial distance from the start. [Allotrope]
A repetition setting is a control setting that specifies the number of times an action is to be repeated. [Allotrope]

A report is a document assembled by an author for the purpose of providing information for the audience. A report is the output of a documenting process and has the objective to be consumed by a specific audience. Topic of the report is on something that has completed. A report is not a single figure. [IAO]
Examples: patent application; grant progress report; journal article; case report (not patient record)

Definition: A report method is a plan specification that serves as a template to organize the data, results, and method contents in a generated report. The report method is independent of any data that the report contains. [Allotrope]
A reporter data cube is a data cube that represents a plot of reporter dye result against cycle. [Allotrope]

Reporter dye role is the role of a dye in a PCR experiment that binds to target DNA molecules and is detected via fluorescence when it is cleaved free. The fluorescence signal is proportional to DNA concentration. [Allotrope]
A reporter dye setting is a setting that classifies the reporter dye used in the PCR experiment. [Allotrope]
Reporting is an information process that produces a report. [Allotrope]
A representation form is a type of information content entity that represents an entity in a certain way. [Allotrope]
Examples: plot as representation form of a temperature profile

Definition: A list used to sequence objects and to line up requests for a resource. [NCI]
A requirement is a proposition that states a set of conditions that have to be fulfilled to achieve some specific objective. [Allotrope]
ScopeNote: The goal can be stated in a prescriptive (laws) or directive (plans) way. [Allotrope]

Definition: A researcher is the role of an organizational entity that researches something. [Allotrope]
The reservoir is a container that stores solutions. [Allotrope]
A reservoir temperature is a quantity facet that quantifies the temperature of some reservoir. [Allotrope]
A reset command is a process command that causes a transition to the idle state. [Allotrope]

Resolution is a description of the smallest change in a quality being measured by a sensor (measurement instrument, detector) that causes a perceptible change in the corresponding indication. [Allotrope]
Source: International Vocabulary of Metrology – Basic and General Concepts and Associated Terms (VIM 3rd edition) JCGM 200:2012

Definition: Resolution is the quality of a sensor (measurement instrument, detector) to be able to measure the smallest change in a qualities that causes a perceptible change in the corresponding indication. [Allotrope]
Source: International Vocabulary of Metrology – Basic and General Concepts and Associated Terms (VIM 3rd edition) JCGM 200:2012

Definition: A Resource Unit is a unit for measuring the amount of various types of resources.
A restart command is a process command that orders the procedural element to execute the restarting logic to safely return to the running state. [Allotrope]
A state when material object keeps its spatial location and orientation. [Allotrope]
Result role is a data output role that applies to new information produced by a process. [Allotrope]
A participant specification that specifies a information objects that have the contextual role of a result in the realized process. [Allotrope]
A result specification is a specification of acceptable limits for a result or set of results. [Allotrope]

A resume command is a process command that orders a procedural element that has paused at a programmed transition as the result of either a pause command or a single step mode to resume execution. [Allotrope]
The retentate role is the role of the material that is retained by a filtration process. [Allotrope]
Source: PAC, 1972, 31, 577 (Manual of Symbols and Terminology for Physicochemical Quantities and Units, Appendix II: Definitions, Terminology and Symbols in Colloid and Surface Chemistry) on page 608

Definition: Retention time is a chromatography peak facet that indicates the elapsed time between the injection of the sample and the maximum detector response attributed to the peak (analyte band). [Allotrope]
The retention time window lower offset is the extent of the retention time window in time units below the target retention time. [PSI/MS]
ScopeNote: The lower and upper offsets may be asymmetric about the target time. [PSI/MS]

Definition: The retention time window upper offset is the extent of the retention time window in time units above the target retention time. [PSI/MS]
ScopeNote: The lower and upper offsets may be asymmetric about the target time. [PSI/MS]

Definition: The retention time window width it the full width of a retention time window for a chromatographic peak. [PSI/MS]
Retention volume is a chromatography peak facet that indicates the acquisition volume at the maximum detector response attributed to the peak (analyte band). [Allotrope]

Retention volume is the volume of the mobile phase required to elute a component the concentration of which in the stationary phase is negligible compared to that in the mobile phase. In other words, this component is not retained at all by the stationary phase. Thus, the hold-up volume is equal to the retention volume of an unretained compound. The hold-up volume includes any volumes contributed by the sample injector, the detector, and connectors.  In gas chromatography this term is also called the gas hold-up volume. The corrected gas hold-up volume is the gas hold-up volume multiplied by the compression (compressibility) correction factor. [IUPAC]
The retriever is an agent role in an audit trail who pulled the record from somewhere. [Allotrope]

Definition: A separation method where the components are distributed between two phases, one of which is stationary and non-polar, while the other is polar and moves in a definite direction. [CHMO]

AltLabels: reversed phase high-performance liquid chromatography; reverse phase  high performance liquid chromatography; RHPLC; RP-HPLC; reversed-phase high-pressure liquid chromatography; gradient reverse HPLC; reversed-phase high pressure liquid chromatography; gradient reverse high-performance liquid chromatography; reversed-phase HPLC
Definition: Liquid chromatography where the inlet pressure is relatively high and the mobile phase is significantly more polar than the stationary phase (which consists of very small particles), for example a microporous silica-based material with chemically bonded alkyl chains. [CHMO]
Liquid chromatography where the mobile phase is significantly more polar than the stationary phase, for example a microporous silica-based material with chemically bonded alkyl chains. [CHMO]
A critical assessment of an electronic record or the changes thereof. [Allotrope]
A reviewer is the role of an agent that reviews some information. [Allotrope]
The reviewer is an agent role in an audit trail who assessed changes to an electronic record. [Allotrope]
A revision record dataset is an audit record dataset that contains the metadata and data that is needed to record revisions of an electronic record in an activity. [Allotrope]
The study of the flow of fluids which cannot be defined by a single value of viscosity. Rheometry is the measurement of the relationship between deformation and stress for these liquids. [CHMO]

A right unbounded selection is a dimension selection on a dimension which represents an ordinal scale. A right unbounded selection must define a minimum. [Allotrope]

Definition: The rinse solution role is a cleaning agent role of a fluid used to flush something in order to remove contaminants. [Allotrope]
Rinsing is the process of washing quickly a device with a solution. [Allotrope]

B is a role means: b is a realizable entity and b exists because there is some single bearer that is in some special physical, social, or institutional set of circumstances in which this bearer does not have to be and b is not such that, if it ceases to exist, then the physical make-up of the bearer is thereby changed. [BFO]
Examples: the role of subject in a clinical trial; the student role; the role of a building in serving as a military target; the priest role; the role of a stone in marking a property boundary; John’s role of husband to Mary is dependent on Mary’s role of wife to John, and both are dependent on the object aggregate comprising John and Mary as member parts joined together through the relational quality of being married.; the role of a boundary to demarcate two neighboring administrative territories

Definition: A role class datum is a classification datum that classifies an entity by the role or contextual role class it plays in the context of the classification datum. [Allotrope]
A role coordination is a class coordination of a class with the class of general role its instances have. [Allotrope]
Examples: A reference column is a class of columns that have an reference role. [Allotrope]

Definition: A specification that specifies a participant in a process by the general role it plays in it. [Allotrope]
A room is a site that is a part or division of a building enclosed by walls, floor, and ceiling. [Allotrope]
A rotational speed is a quality quantification facet that quantifies some rotational speed. [Allotrope]
A rotational speed is a movement quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's frequency of rotation. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: is executing; executing state; running; is running; executing
Definition: A running state is a state during which a device or service performs its specified function in normal operation. [Allotrope]
A sample aggregate document is a document that is about an ordered collection of samples. [Allotrope]
A sample document is a document about a particular sample. [Allotrope]
A sample flow rate data cube is a data cube that represents the flow rate through the sample pump of a chromatograph. [Allotrope]
A sample flow rate profile is a flow rate profile of the flow rate through the sample pump of the chromatograph. [Allotrope]
Sample id is a measurement metadata that identifies a sample being measured. [Allotrope]
A sample inlet is an in port of a measurement or separation device where sample material is passing in to the device. [Allotrope]
A sample introduction is a loading of some sample into a system. [Allotrope]
A sample introduction description is a description that describes the process of sample introduction. [Allotrope]
A sample introduction document is a document that encompasses the information associated with the process of sample introduction. [Allotrope]
A sample introduction medium designates the material type that is used as medium (role) in a sample introduction process in a measurement. [Allotrope]
Examples: Acetonitrile as the solvent in liquid chromatography, or nitrogen as the carrier gas in gas chromatography.

Definition: A sample introduction medium is the role of a material that carries the sample in a sample introduction process. [Allotrope]
A sample introduction mode setting is a control setting that specifies the type of sample introduction process to be used, which is the process of loading the sample into a system. [Allotrope]
A sample measurement interface is a connecting device through which measurements are captured. [Allotrope]

A sample pan role is the role of the measurement pan realized in a DSC measurement that contains the sample. [Allotrope]
A sample passage is the compartment of a device that handles the conveying of samples. [Allotrope]

Definition: Sample preparation is a planned preparation process that synthesizes, converts or changes a sample. [Allotrope]

A sample preparation description is a description of the sample preparation process. [Allotrope]
A sample preparation document is a document about a sample preparation process. [Allotrope]
A sample role is a type of role whose bearer is a material entity that is the output of a sampling. [Allotrope]
A sample role (preparation) is a role of a portion of material that is prepared for bearing the sample role in an experiment. [Allotrope]
A sample role type is a classification datum that classifies samples by the type of  sample role in the experiment. [Allotrope]
The sample set role is the role of the partition of the population object aggregate that was selected in the sampling process. [Allotrope]
A sample shape classification is a classification datum that classifies the shape of the sample undergoing testing. [Allotrope]
Sample suspension media is a description that describes the suspension media used in preparation of the sample. [Allotrope]
A sample temperature result is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the temperature of the sample. [Allotrope]
A sample temperature setting is a temperature control setting to set the target temperature of the sample. [Allotrope]
A sample thickness is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the thickness of some sample. [Allotrope]
A sample volume setting is a control setting specifying the volume of sample to be used in a measurement. [Allotrope]
Sample weight is a quantification facet that quantifies the mass of a sample in an analysis. [Allotrope]

A sample width is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the horizontal length of a sample at the point of measurement. [Allotrope]
A sample is a device that function to sample known amounts of material. [Allotrope]

A saturated gas flow rate is a flow rate that quantifies the motion of the saturated gas over time. [Allotrope]

is part of a mapping and maps exactly one scale of a corresponding data structure definition from technical indices to scale values. [Allotrope]

A scan position setting is a setting that specifies whether the detector is positioned underneath the microplate. [Allotrope]
A scan speed setting is a control setting that specifies the speed at which the radiation beam scans some sample. [Allotrope]
Scanning is measuring repeatedly or sweepingly. [Allotrope]

The measurement of thermodynamic parameters (e.g. enthalpy) during a chemical or biochemical reaction by the known variation (step-wise or linear) of one variable, whilst a second is kept constant. [CHMO]

Scattering is a general physical process where some forms of radiation, such as light, sound, or moving particles, are forced to deviate from a straight trajectory by one or more paths due to localized non-uniformities in the medium through which they pass. [Wikipedia]
Any method that measures the amount of light that a substance scatters at certain wavelengths, incident angles, and polarization angles. [CHMO]
A seal initiation temperature is the temperature at which a seal is initiated, determined by the seal's strength reaching 4 Newtons. [Allotrope]
A secant modulus is the slope of a line from the origin of a stress-strain curve intersecting at a given strain value. [Allotrope]
A secant modulus aggregate document is a document that is about a collection of secant modulus documents. [Allotrope]
A secant modulus document is a document that encompasses the information associated with a secant modulus. [Allotrope]
A section is a site that is a more or less distinct part of a site into which the site is divided. [Allotrope]
A device that is selected to perform a specific function in a process. [Allotrope]

A plot of ion current vs. retention time obtained from a chromatography experiment with mass detection. A small mass window is monitored such that the mass chromatogram represents detection of a very specific mass-to-charge ratio. [CHMO]
Selected ion monitoring is mass spectrometry where the abundances of ions of one or more specific m/z values are recorded rather than the entire mass spectrum. [IUPAC]
Source: K. K. Murray, R. K. Boyd, M. N. Eberlin, G. J. Langley, L. Li and Y. Naito, Pure Appl. Chem., 2013, 85, 1515-1609

Definition: A selected-ion monitoring (SIM) chromatogram is similar to an XIC, with the exception that the mass spectrometer is operated in SIM mode, such that only preselected m/z values are detected in the analysis. [Wikipedia]
A selected ion profile is an ion profile where only preselected m/z values are detected in the analysis. [Allotrope]
A selected object is the selection role of the object that is selected from the selection target. [Allotrope]

Selected reaction monitoring is a multiple-stage mass spectrometry where data acquired from one or more specific product ions corresponding to m/z selected precursor ions are recorded via two or more stages of mass spectrometry. [IUPAC]
Source: E. de Hoffmann (1996). Tandem Mass Spectrometry: a Primer. Journal of Mass Spectrometry 31: 129–137.

Definition: Selected reaction monitoring is a multiple-stage mass spectrometry where data acquired from one or more specific product ions corresponding to m/z selected precursor ions are recorded via two or more stages of mass spectrometry. [IUPAC]
Source: K. K. Murray, R. K. Boyd, M. N. Eberlin, G. J. Langley, L. Li and Y. Naito, Pure Appl. Chem., 2013, 85, 1515-1609

Definition: The partitioning of some object aggregate. [Allotrope]

(1) A subset of a dataset or a dataspace, up to the entire dataset of dataspace.
(2) The elements of an array or dataset that are marked for I/O. [HDF]
A role which is played by a participant in a selection process. [Allotrope]
A selection structure definition is a set of component selections on the  components of a data structure definition. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: selection population; selection set; selection target
Definition: The selection target is the role of a participant in a selection process from which partitions are selected. [Allotrope]
A viability quality inhering in a population by virtue of some of it's members' ability to survive. [PATO]
The role inhered in a material entity that sends the transferred object in a transfer process. [Allotrope]
A process that transports a signal across a system boundary out of the system. [Allotrope]
The state of perceiving or becoming aware of a signal. [Allotrope]
A sensor is a component of a measuring system that is directly affected by a phenomenon, body, or substance carrying a quantity to be measured. [Allotrope]
Sent object is the role of a transferred object at the start of the transferring process. [Allotrope]
A branching process that isolates flows into distinct component flows. The separated components are distinct from the flow before separation, as well as each other. [NIST]
A separating of materials. [Allotrope]
A separation aggregate document is a document that aggregates separation documents. [Allotrope]
A separation column is a separation device of columnar shape where the separation occurs inside the column. [Allotrope]
A device that has the function to separate materials. [Allotrope]
A separation document is a document that encompasses the information associated with some separating process. [Allotrope]
An experiment in which a separation method is coupled to a detection method in order to detect one or more different components of a sample. [CHMO]
A workflow role of a single step in a sequentially executed procedure. [Allotrope]
Examples: A single data acquisition of a data acquisition profile.

Definition: A sequential analysis process is a planned sequential process that has analytical subprocesses as sequential occurrent parts. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: event table; linear procedure specification; sequence specification
Definition: A procedure specification with a linear ordered collection of action specifications. [Allotrope]

A sequential process is a composite process that has sequential subprocesses as occurrent parts. The starts of all subprocesses occur in sequential order. The ends of all subprocesses occur at the end of the sequential process at the latest. [Allotrope]

A serial number is an information content entity which is a unique sequence of characters borne by part of manufactured product or its packaging that is assigned to each individual in some class of products, and so can serve as a way to identify an individual product within the class. Serial numbers can be encoded in a variety of other information objects, such as bar codes, numerals, or patterns of dots. [IAO]

In computer science, in the context of data storage, a serialization algorithm translates data structures or object states into a format that can be stored (for example, in a file or memory buffer, or transmitted across a network connection link) and reconstructed later in the same or another computer environment. [Allotrope]
A series is a list (ordered collection) of literal values. [Allotrope]
An individual entry in a series with an index and a numeric value. [Allotrope]
A server is a computer which provides some service for other computers connected to it via a network. [NCI]
A server identifier is an identifier that identifies some server. [Allotrope]
A collection where each member is disjoint from another. [Allotrope]
A setting is a specification about a configuration of some controllable system or a situation occurring in a system that triggers a reaction. [Allotrope]
Examples: A maximum pressure in a plumbing system that triggers a warning.; A temperature that is that target temperature setting of a thermostat.

Definition: Setting datum is the contextual role of an information object that specifies some device or process setting. [Allotrope]
A setting snapshot is a setting for a specific point in time. [Allotrope]
Shaking is a mixing process involving short rapid motions of the material inside a container. [Allotrope]
A shaking configuration description is a description of the shaking process configuration. [Allotrope]
A morphological quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's ratios of distances between its features (points, edges, surfaces and also holes etc). [PATO]
Shaping is changing the material in regard to spatial form. [Allotrope]
A shaping device is a conversion device that alters the shape of some material. [Allotrope]
Shear modulus is a ratio of shear stress to the shear strain. It is a quantity for measuring the stiffness of materials. The shear modulus is concerned with the deformation of a material. [Wikipedia]
A zero shear modulus is a determinate shear modulus with zero magnitude. [Allotrope]
A shear strain is parallel to the face of an element. [Wikipedia]

A shearing force is applied to the top of the rectangle while the bottom is held in place. The resulting shear stress deforms the rectangle into a parallelogram. The area involved would be the top of the parallelogram. A shear stress is the component of stress coplanar with a material cross section. [Wikipedia]

AltLabels: shoulder detection enabled setting; enable shoulder detection; detect shoulders on/off
Definition: Shoulder detection enabled setting is a  data processing setting that allows the integration process to interpolate a baseline for the smaller peak of overlapping peaks for the time period specified. [Allotrope]
Sieve analysis is a process of particle sizing by filtering particles according to their size through sieves with decreasing pore size. [Allotrope]

An information content entity that is an input or output in a process at the boundary of a system. The signal is sent or received via ports of the system. The signal conveys information about the behavior or attributes of some phenomenon. [Allotrope]
A signal is information transported over an communication channel. [Allotrope]
Signal averaging is a process of combining spectra of repeated measurements in order to improve the signal-to-noise ratio. [Allotrope]
A signal configuration is a device configuration of a device producing or consuming signals, that controls the processing of a signal. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: gain setting; amplification setting; amplification; gain; amplification configuration; gain configuration; signal gain setting; signal amplification setting
Definition: A gain setting is a signal configuration, that controls the amplification of an incoming or outgoing signal. [Allotrope]
A signal offset configuration is a signal processing configuration, that adds/subtracts a fixed amount of magnitude to the signal strength or amplitude to move the zero reference. [Allotrope]

PrefLabel: signal to noise calculation enabled setting
Definition: A signal to noise calculation enabled setting is a data processing setting that indicates if signal to noise results are to be calculated. [Allotrope]
A peak facet that ratios the peak height value with background level of noise.  It is an indication of the sensitivity of a particular method toward the analyte that the peak represents. [Allotrope]
A signal-to-noise ratio calculated using the ASTM E1657-98 method. [Allotrope]
Signal-to-noise ratio (EP2.2.46) is a signal-to-noise ratio (peak-to-peak) where the noise is calculated over a period that is a minimum of 20 times the peak width. [Allotrope]
A signal-to-noise ratio calculated using the Root Mean Square noise method. [Allotrope]
Signal-to-noise ratio (USP621) is a signal-to-noise ratio (peak-to-peak) where the noise is calculated over a period that is a minimum of 5 times the peak width. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: signal-to-noise (peak-to-peak, JP-G20); signal-to-noise (peak-to-peak, EP 2.2.46); signal-to-noise (peak-to-peak, USP 621)
Definition: A signal-to-noise ratio calculated using the peak-to-peak noise method. This includes JP-G20 (measured over optimally 20 X peak width at half height but at least 5 times the peak width at half height), EP 2.2.46 (measured over at least 5 times the peak width at half height), USP 621 (measured over at least 5 times the peak width at half height). [Allotrope]
Signaling is the process of providing information on a material, energy or signal flow as an output signal. [NIST]
A signature is facet that is a proof of identity and intent of a signer towards some information. [Allotrope]
An algorithm for creating a digital signature. [Allotrope]
A signature role is the role of an information object that is associated with some information and provides a proof of identity and intent of the signer. [Allotrope]
A signature role type is a classification datum that classifies the signature role of some signature. [Allotrope]
Signed content role is the signing contextual role of the information content entity that is being signed. [Allotrope]
Examples: A contract signed.; An approval signed.

Definition: The signed object is the bearer of the information content entity that is signed. [Allotrope]
Examples: The paper where the signature was written on.

Definition: A signer is a role in an audit trail of a person signing the electronic record. [Allotrope]
A signer is the role of the agent in a signing process. [Allotrope]
A signing is attaching a signature to an information content entity. The signature is an identifier for the agent doing the signing. [Allotrope]
A signing contextual role is a contextual role of information content entities that are participants in a signing process. [Allotrope]
A signing role is a role that is realized in some signing activity. [Allotrope]
A silver nitrate titrant solution is a titrant solution containing silver nitrate as the reactant. [Allotrope]
An silver(1+) ion is a  +1 charged silver cation. [Allotrope]
A single quadrupole mass spectrometer is a type of quadrupole mass spectrometer that uses one single quadrupole field. [Allotrope]
Single quadrupole mass spectrometry is a quadrupole mass spectrometry using a single quadrupole mass analyzer. [Allotrope]
B is a site means: b is a three-dimensional immaterial entity that is (partially or wholly) bounded by a material entity or it is a three-dimensional immaterial part thereof. [BFO]
Examples: your left nostril (a fiat part – the opening – of your left nasal cavity); the interior of a kangaroo pouch; the interior of your bedroom; the interior of your refrigerator; the hold of a ship; a hole in the interior of a portion of cheese; the interior of your office; Manhattan Canyon); the interior of the trunk of your car; an air traffic control region defined in the airspace above an airport; the Grand Canyon; the lumen of your gut; the cockpit of an aircraft; the Piazza San Marco; a rabbit hole

Definition: A site (organization) is a site where organizational entities are located such as an office or premise. [Allotrope]
ScopeNote: An office or other premise at which the organization is located. Many organizations are spread across multiple sites and many sites will host multiple locations. [W3C ORG]

Definition: Portion of reality that is realized in some process. [Allotrope]
A specification of a circumstances (process). [Allotrope]
Size is the number of members of some collection of data. [Allotrope]
Size is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the spatial extend of an entity. [Allotrope]
A morphology quality inhering in a bearer by virtue of the bearer's physical magnitude. [PATO]

Definition: A plot of detector signal (e.g. ion count or  absorbance) vs. retention time obtained from a chromatography experiment where the separation is caused by exclusion effects within the stationary phase and where the stationary phase is a swollen gel. [CHMO]
Column chromatography where the separation is achieved based on differences in molecular size. [CHMO]

Skewness is a descriptive statistic that is a measure of the asymmetry of the probability distribution of a real-valued random variable about its mean. The skewness value can be positive or negative, or undefined. [Wikipedia]

Skewness role is a statistical datum role of a datum that is a measure of the asymmetry of the probability distribution of a real-valued random variable about its mean. The skewness value can be positive or negative, or undefined. [Wikipedia]
A skimmer is a cone with a central orifice that intercepts the center of a spray or jet expansion to sample the central portion of the expansion, for example, as in a momentum separator. [IUPAC]
Source: K. K. Murray, R. K. Boyd, M. N. Eberlin, G. J. Langley, L. Li and Y. Naito, Pure Appl. Chem., 2013, 85, 1515-1609

Definition: A long narrow cut or opening. [Allotrope]
A slit width setting is a setting that specifies the width of the opening of the slit. [Allotrope]
Slope is a mathematical facet of a line that describes both the direction and the steepness of the line. [Wikipedia]
A smoothing window setting is a control setting that specifies the smoothing window for foam detection. [Allotrope]
A snapshot is the contextual role of an information object that is about a point in time within the bounds of a process. [Allotrope]
A sodium analysis document (cell-culture) is a document that encompasses the information associated with sodium. [Allotrope]
A sodium hydroxide titrant solution is a titrant solution containing sodium hydroxide as the reactant. [Allotrope]
An indirect association between a name and an object in an HDF5 file. [Allotrope]
Software is a plan specification composed of a series of instructions that can be interpreted by or directly executed by a processing unit. [IAO]
A software agent is the contextual role of software in the context of a process where a system executes that software and causally is an agent in the process. [Allotrope]
A software name is a name of some software. [Allotrope]
A version number that identifies software. [Allotrope]
A sol is a fluid colloidal system of two or more components. [IUPAC]
Source: PAC, 2007, 79, 1801 (Definitions of terms relating to the structure and processing of sols, gels, networks, and inorganic-organic hybrid materials (IUPAC Recommendations 2007)) on page 1805

Definition: A solid is a substance that is in the solid material state. [Allotrope]

A state of matter, in which particles are closely packed together. The forces between particles are strong so that the particles cannot move freely but can only vibrate. As a result, a solid has a stable, definite shape, and a definite volume. Solids can only change their shape by force, as when broken or cut. [Wikipedia]
A solid aerosol is an colloid where the continuous phase is a gas and the dispersed phase is a solid. [Allotrope]
Source: Everett, D. (2009). Manual of Symbols and Terminology for Physicochemical Quantities and Units, Appendix II: Definitions, Terminology and Symbols in Colloid and Surface Chemistry. Pure and Applied Chemistry, 31(4), pp. 577-638.

Definition: A substance having definite shape and volume manufactured for the administration of active and/or inert ingredient(s). Solids include tablets, capsules, powders, granules and certain suppositories. [NCI]
A solid foam is a colloid where the continuous phase is a solid and the dispersed phase is a gas. [Allotrope]
A solid heterogeneous mixture is a heterogeneous mixture in solid state. [Allotrope]
A solid in liquid solution is a solution where the continuous phase is a solid and the dispersed phase is a liquid. [Allotrope]
Examples: salt or sugar in water

Definition: A solid in solid solution is a solution where the continuous phase is a solid and the dispersed phase is a solid. [Allotrope]
Examples: alloys

Definition: A solid sol is a colloid where the continuous phase is a solid and the dispersed phase is a solid. [Allotrope]
The state of material becoming solid from liquid. [Allotrope]

Definition: Solute is the role a portion of material when it is dissolved within a solution. [Allotrope]
A solution is a homogeneous mixture composed of one phase where particles  are not visible to the naked eye and the solution does not scatter a light beam. [Allotrope]
Source: Orange Book: IUPAC Compendium of Analytical Nomenclature. Second Edition, Blackwell Scientific Publications, Oxford, 1987.

Definition: A solution is a homogeneous mixture composed of one phase where particles  are not visible to the naked eye and the solution does not scatter a light beam. [Allotrope]
Source: PAC, 1994, 66, 533 (Standard quantities in chemical thermodynamics. Fugacities, activities and equilibrium constants for pure and mixed phases (IUPAC Recommendations 1994))

Definition: A solution analyzer aggregate document is a document that aggregates solution analyzer documents. [Allotrope]
A solution analyzer document is a document that encompasses the information associated with some solution analyzer run. [Allotrope]

A solution-state nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy is a nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy where the response of nuclei with non-zero spin, in a sample dissolved in a deuterated solvent, to a perturbing magnetic field is detected. Each experiment consists of a sequence of radio frequency pulses with delay periods in between them. [CHMO]

PrefLabel: solution-state nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy aggregate document
AltLabels: solution-state NMR aggregate document; solution-state NMR spectroscopy aggregate document
Definition: A solution-state nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy aggregate document is a document that aggregates solution-state nuclear magnetic resonance documents. [Allotrope]

PrefLabel: solution-state nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy document
AltLabels: solution-state NMR document; solution-state NMR spectroscopy document
Definition: A solution-state nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy document is a document that encompasses the information associated with a solution-state nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy run. [Allotrope]
A solvent channel is a channel where a liquid can flow through. [Allotrope]
Examples: A quaternary pump has 4 channels.

Definition: A solvent identifier is an identifier denoting the solvent used in the experiment. [Allotrope]
A solvent reservoir temperature is a quantity facet that quantifies the temperature of the solvent reservoir. [Allotrope]
Solvent is the role of a potion of liquid material when it dissolves a solute in order to produce a solution. [Allotrope]

The irradiation of a liquid sample with sound (20-20 000 Hz) waves resulting in agitation. Sound waves propagate into the liquid media result in alternating high-pressure (compression) and low-pressure (rarefaction) cycles. During rarefaction, high-intensity sonic waves create small vacuum bubbles or voids in the liquid, which then collapse violently (cavitation) during compression, creating very high local temperatures. [CHMO]
A sonication duration setting is a duration setting that specifies the duration of a sonication process before analysis. [Allotrope]
A sonication power setting is a setting that specifies the power of a sonication process. [Allotrope]

A method for determining surface area by measuring the amount of an inert gaseous or liquid substance (the 'sorbent', usually H2 or N2) which adsorbs onto the surface of interest (the 'sorbate'), and the subsequent amount that desorbs at a constant temperature. Regression analysis is then applied to the data, resulting in an isotherm. [CHMO]
Sorting is distributing flows based on some associated physical quality or entity into distinct fractions according to a defined order. [Allotrope]
Sorting is the dividing of material by an ordering criteria. [Allotrope]
An entity that plays the source role is an entity that is being derived or quoted. [Allotrope]
A source current setting is a current setting controlling the current supplied to a radiation source. [Allotrope]
A space is a site that can be occupied or where something can be done. [Allotrope]
ScopeNote: Space is especially viewed in terms of whether there is enough. [Allotrope]

Definition: A spatial region is a continuant entity that is a continuant part of space R as defined relative to some frame R. [BFO]
A spatial role is the contextual role of some information context object that is about spatial location, orientation, or relative positioning. [Allotrope]
Examples: left, right, above, below, inside, outside, parallel

Definition: A spatial state is a state that is expressed by a spatial location or orientation of some material participating in the state. [Allotrope]
Spatio-temporal role is a type of contextual role of an information artifact that denotes an entity in a spatio-temporal context. [Allotrope]
A spatiotemporal region is an occurrent entity that is part of spacetime. [BFO]
Examples: the spatiotemporal region occupied by the development of a cancer tumor; the spatiotemporal region occupied by a human life; the spatiotemporal region occupied by a process of cellular meiosis.

AltLabels: specific entropy of fusion (datum); specific heat of fusion
Definition: The specific enthalpy of fusion datum is the enthalpy of fusion referenced to a unit mass of substance. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: specific latent heat of melting; specific enthalpy of melting (quality); specific heat of melting; specific enthalpy of melting; specific enthalpy of fusion
Definition: The specific enthalpy of fusion is the enthalpy of fusion referenced to a unit mass of substance. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: specific heat of sublimation; specific enthalpy of sublimation (datum)
Definition: The specific enthalpy of sublimation datum is the enthalpy of sublimation referenced to a unit mass of substance. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: specific heat of sublimation; specific enthalpy of sublimation
Definition: The specific enthalpy of sublimation is the enthalpy of sublimation referenced to a unit mass of substance. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: specific enthalpy of vaporization (datum); specific heat of vaporization
Definition: The specific enthalpy of vaporization datum is the enthalpy of vaporization referenced to a unit mass of substance. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: specific heat of vaporization; specific heat of evaporation; specific latent heat of vaporization
Definition: The specific enthalpy of vaporization is the enthalpy of vaporization referenced to a unit mass of substance. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: specific heat capacity (datum); specific heat capacity result
Definition: A specific heat capacity (datum) is a quality quantification facet that quantifies the amount of heat necessary to raise the temperature of one gram of a pure substance by one degree K. [Wikipedia]
A specific heat capacity (quality) is a heat capacity of a pure substance by virtue of the amount of heat necessary to raise the temperature per amount of mass. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: specific rotation result; specific optical rotation
Definition: A specific rotation result is is a quality quantification facet quantifying the change in orientation of monochromatic plane-polarized light, per unit distance–concentration product, as the light passes through a sample of a compound in solution. [Wikipedia]

Specific rotation is the change in orientation of monochromatic plane-polarized light, per unit distance–concentration product, as the light passes through a sample of a compound in solution. [Wikipedia]
A specific rotation document is a document about a polarimetry process used to measure a specific rotation. [Allotrope]

When the area of the interface between two phases is proportional to the mass of one of the phases (e.g. for a solid adsorbent, for an emulsion or for an aerosol), the specific surface area (a, s or preferably as) is defined as the surface area divided by the mass of the relevant phase. [IUPAC]
Source: PAC, 1972, 31, 577. (Manual of Symbols and Terminology for Physicochemical Quantities and Units, Appendix II: Definitions, Terminology and Symbols in Colloid and Surface Chemistry)

Definition: A property of solids defined as the total surface area of a material per unit mass or volume.

b is a specifically dependent continuant if b is a continuant and there is some independent continuant c which is not a spatial region and which is such that b specifically depends on c at every time t during the course of b’s existence. [BFO]
Examples: the mutual dependence of proton donors and acceptors in chemical reactions [79; the smell of this portion of mozzarella; of one-sided specifically dependent continuants: the mass of this tomato; the mutual dependence of the role predator and the role prey as played by two organisms in a given interaction; the disposition of this fish to decay; of relational dependent continuants (multiple bearers): John’s love for Mary, the ownership relation between John and this statue, the relation of authority between John and his subordinates.; Reciprocal specifically dependent continuants: the function of this key to open this lock and the mutually dependent disposition of this lock: to be opened by this key; the function of this heart: to pump blood; the role of being a doctor; the pink color of a medium rare piece of grilled filet mignon at its center; the shape of this hole.

Definition: A specification is a proposition about the intended purpose or design of an entity. [Allotrope]
A specification assessment is an assessment about whether some result conforms to a predefined specification. [Allotrope]
A specification coordination is a subject coordination of a subclass of directive information class. [Allotrope]
Examples: Volume concentration setting is a setting that specifies the volume concentration.

Definition: A specification target is the role of a material entity that participates in a specifying process and is what the resulting specification is about. [Allotrope]
Specified action is the role of information object that specifies an activity. [Allotrope]
Specified capability is the contextual role of an information object that specifies a capability. [Allotrope]

A degradation product role that is individually listed and limited with a specific acceptance criterion in the new drug product specification. A specified degradation product can be either identified or unidentified. [ICH-Q3A]

An impurity that is individually listed and limited with aspecific acceptance criterion in the new drug substance specification. A specified impurity can be either identified or unidentified. [ICH-Q3A]
Specified procedure is the contextual role of an information object that specifies a flow of activities. [Allotrope]
Specified profile is the contextual role of an information object that specifies a process profile. [Allotrope]
A specified quality is the contextual role of an information object that describes a quality as part of an specification. [Allotrope]
A specified situation is the contextual role of an information object that describes a portion of reality as part of a specification. [Allotrope]

Specifying is a process that produces an information object which describes constraints or objectives on characteristics like qualities, functions, dispositions, facets of continuants or processes. [Allotrope]
Specimen role is the sample role of a prepared fraction of a portion of material that is analyzed in a particular experiment. [Allotrope]
Spectra combination is a data transformation that combines multiple spectra. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: library search hit; search hit; hit
Definition: A spectral library search hit is a result of a library search where a record matches some search criteria. [Allotrope]

AltLabels: library search result; library search report
Definition: A spectral library search result is a report that lists the hits on search in a spectral library database. [Allotrope]
A spectral width setting is a nuclear magnetic resonance setting that describes the range over which data is to be collected. [Allotrope]
A piece of apparatus used to measure a spectrum. [CHMO]
A spectrometer type is a classification datum that classifies the type of spectrometer used in a process. [Allotrope]
Spectrometry is the measurement of such radiations as a means of obtaining information about the systems and their components. [IUPAC]
Source: IUPAC. Compendium of Chemical Terminology, 2nd ed. (the "Gold Book"). Compiled by A. D. McNaught and A. Wilkinson. Blackwell Scientific Publications, Oxford (1997). Online version (2019-) created by S. J. Chalk. ISBN 0-9678550-9-8. https://doi.org/10.1351/goldbook.

Definition: A spectrophotometer is a photometer that measures the intensity of light at each individual wavelength. [Allotrope]
